# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: archias-of-pella
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Three centuries after the decline of Mycenaean Greece during the Bronze Age collapse, Greek urban poleis began to form in the 8th century BC, ushering in the Archaic period and the colonization of the Mediterranean Basin.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] This was followed by the age of Classical Greece, from the Greco-Persian Wars to the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC, and which included the Golden Age of Athens and the Peloponnesian War between Athens and Sparta.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The unification of Greece by Macedon under Philip II and subsequent conquest of the Achaemenid Empire by Alexander the Great spread Hellenistic civilization across the Middle East.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period is considered to have ended in 30 BC, when the last Hellenistic kingdom, Ptolemaic Egypt, was annexed by the Roman Republic.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Classical Greek culture, especially philosophy, had a powerful influence on ancient Rome, which carried a version of it throughout the Mediterranean and much of Europe.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] For this reason, Classical Greece is generally considered the cradle of Western civilization, the seminal culture from which the modern West derives many of its founding archetypes and ideas in politics, philosophy, science, and art.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in the Mediterranean region is commonly considered to have begun in the 8th century BC (around the time of the earliest recorded poetry of Homer) and ended in the 6th century AD.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in Greece was preceded by the Greek Dark Ages (c.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] 800 BC), archaeologically characterised by the protogeometric and geometric styles of designs on pottery.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Following the Dark Ages was the Archaic period, beginning around the 8th century BC, which saw early developments in Greek culture and society leading to the Classical period from the Persian invasion of Greece in 480 BC until the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Classical period is characterized by a "classical" style, i.e. one which was considered exemplary by later observers, most famously in the Parthenon of Athens.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Politically, the Classical period was dominated by Athens and the Delian League during the 5th century, but displaced by Spartan hegemony during the early 4th century BC, before power shifted to Thebes and the Boeotian League and finally to the League of Corinth led by Macedon.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] This period was shaped by the Greco-Persian Wars, the Peloponnesian War, and the Rise of Macedon.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Following the Classical period was the Hellenistic period (323–146 BC), during which Greek culture and power expanded into the Near East from the death of Alexander until the Roman conquest.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Roman Greece is usually counted from the Roman victory over the Corinthians at the Battle of Corinth in 146 BC to the establishment of Byzantium by Constantine as the capital of the Roman Empire in 330 AD.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Finally, Late Antiquity refers to the period of Christianization during the later 4th to early 6th centuries AD, consummated by the closure of the Academy of Athens by Justinian I in 529.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The historical period of ancient Greece is unique in world history as the first period attested directly in comprehensive, narrative historiography, while earlier ancient history or protohistory is known from much more fragmentary documents such as annals, king lists, and pragmatic epigraphy.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Herodotus is widely known as the "father of history": his *Histories* are eponymous of the entire field.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Written between the 450s and 420s BC, Herodotus' work reaches about a century into the past, discussing 6th-century BC historical figures such as Darius I of Persia, Cambyses II and Psamtik III, and alluding to some 8th-century BC persons such as Candaules.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The accuracy of Herodotus' works is debated.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Herodotus was succeeded by authors such as Thucydides, Xenophon, Demosthenes, Plato and Aristotle.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Most were either Athenian or pro-Athenian, which is why far more is known about the history and politics of Athens than of many other cities.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Their scope is further limited by a focus on political, military and diplomatic history, ignoring economic and social history.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The archaic period, lasting approximately from 800 to 500 BC, saw the culmination of political and social developments which had begun in the Greek Dark Age, with the *polis* (city-state) becoming the most important unit of political organisation in Greece.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The absence of powerful states in Greece after the collapse of Mycenaean power, and the geography of Greece, where many settlements were separated from their neighbours by mountainous terrain, encouraged the development of small independent city-states.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Several Greek states saw tyrants rise to power in this period, most famously at Corinth from 657 BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The period also saw the founding of Greek colonies around the Mediterranean, with Euboean settlements at Al-Mina in the east as early as 800 BC, and Ischia in the west by 775.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Increasing contact with non-Greek peoples in this period, especially in the Near East, inspired developments in art and architecture, the adoption of coinage, and the development of the Greek alphabet.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Athens developed its democratic system over the course of the archaic period.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Already in the 7th century, the right of all citizen men to attend the assembly appears to have been established.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] After a failed coup led by Cylon of Athens around 636 BC, Draco was appointed to establish a code of laws in 621.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] This failed to reduce the political tension between the poor and the elites, and in 594 Solon was given the authority to enact another set of reforms, which attempted to balance the power of the rich and the poor.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the middle of the 6th century, Pisistratus established himself as a tyrant, and after his death in 527 his son Hippias inherited his position; by the end of the 6th century he had been overthrown, and Cleisthenes carried out further democratising reforms.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In Sparta, a political system with two kings, a council of elders, and five ephors developed over the course of the 8th and 7th centuries.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] According to Spartan tradition, this constitution was established by the legendary lawgiver Lycurgus.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Over the course of the First Messenian War and Second Messenian War, Sparta subjugated the neighbouring region of Messenia, enserfing the population.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the 6th century, Greek city-states began to develop formal relationships with one another, where previously individual rulers had relied on personal relationships with the elites of other cities.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Towards the end of the Archaic period, Sparta began to build a series of alliances, the Peloponnesian League, with cities including Corinth, Elis, and Megara, isolating Messenia and reinforcing Sparta's position against Argos, the other major power in the Peloponnese.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Other alliances in the 6th century included those between Elis and Heraea in the Peloponnese; and between the Greek colony Sybaris in southern Italy, its allies, and the Serdaioi.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In 499 BC, the Ionian city-states under Persian rule rebelled against their Persian-supported tyrant rulers.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Supported by troops sent from Athens and Eretria, they advanced as far as Sardis and burnt the city before being driven back by a Persian counterattack.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The revolt continued until 494, when the rebelling Ionians were defeated.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Darius did not forget that Athens had assisted the Ionian revolt, and in 490 he assembled an armada to retaliate.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Though heavily outnumbered, the Athenians—supported by their Plataean allies—defeated the Persian hordes at the Battle of Marathon, and the Persian fleet turned tail.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Ten years later, a second invasion was launched by Darius' son Xerxes.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The city-states of northern and central Greece submitted to the Persian forces without resistance, but a coalition of 31 Greek city-states, including Athens and Sparta, determined to resist the Persian invaders.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] At the same time, Greek Sicily was invaded by a Carthaginian force.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Persians were decisively defeated at sea by a primarily Athenian naval force at the Battle of Salamis, and on land in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The alliance against Persia continued, initially led by the Spartan Pausanias but from 477 by Athens, and by 460 Persia had been driven out of the Aegean.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] During this long campaign, the Delian League gradually transformed from a defensive alliance of Greek states into an Athenian empire, as Athens' growing naval power intimidated the other league states.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Athens ended its campaigns against Persia in 450, after a disastrous defeat in Egypt in 454, and the death of Cimon in action against the Persians on Cyprus in 450.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] As the Athenian fight against the Persian empire waned, conflict grew between Athens and Sparta.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Suspicious of the increasing Athenian power funded by the Delian League, Sparta offered aid to reluctant members of the League to rebel against Athenian domination.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] These tensions were exacerbated in 462 BC when Athens sent a force to aid Sparta in overcoming a helot revolt, but this aid was rejected by the Spartans.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the 450s, Athens took control of Boeotia, and won victories over Aegina and Corinth.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] However, Athens failed to win a decisive victory, and in 447 lost Boeotia again.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Athens and Sparta signed the Thirty Years' Peace in the winter of 446/445, ending the conflict.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Despite the treaty, Athenian relations with Sparta declined again in the 430s, and in 431 BC the Peloponnesian War began.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The first phase of the war saw a series of fruitless annual invasions of Attica by Sparta, while Athens successfully fought the Corinthian empire in northwest Greece and defended its own empire, despite a plague which killed the leading Athenian statesman Pericles.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The war turned after Athenian victories led by Cleon at Pylos and Sphakteria, and Sparta sued for peace, but the Athenians rejected the proposal.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Athenian failure to regain control of Boeotia at Delium and Brasidas' successes in northern Greece in 424 improved Sparta's position after Sphakteria.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] After the deaths of Cleon and Brasidas, the strongest proponents of war on each side, a peace treaty was negotiated in 421 by the Athenian general Nicias.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In 418 BC allied forces of Athens and Argos were defeated by Sparta at Mantinea.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In 415 Athens launched an ambitious naval expedition to dominate Sicily; the expedition ended in disaster at the harbor of Syracuse, with almost the entire army killed, and the ships destroyed.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Soon after the Athenian defeat in Syracuse, Athens' Ionian allies began to rebel against the Delian league, while Persia began to once again involve itself in Greek affairs on the Spartan side.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Initially the Athenian position continued relatively strong, with important victories at Cyzicus in 410 and Arginusae in 406.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] However, in 405 the Spartan Lysander defeated Athens in the Battle of Aegospotami, and began to blockade Athens' harbour; driven by hunger, Athens sued for peace, agreeing to surrender their fleet and join the Spartan-led Peloponnesian League.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Following the Athenian surrender, Sparta installed an oligarchic regime, the Thirty Tyrants, in Athens, one of a number of Spartan-backed oligarchies which rose to power after the Peloponnesian war.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Spartan predominance did not last: after only a year, the Thirty had been overthrown.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The first half of the 4th century saw the major Greek states attempt to dominate the mainland; none were successful, and their resulting weakness led to a power vacuum which was eventually filled by Macedon under Philip II and then Alexander the Great.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the immediate aftermath of the Peloponnesian war, Sparta attempted to extend their own power, leading Argos, Athens, Corinth, and Thebes to join against them.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Aiming to prevent any single Greek state gaining the dominance that would allow it to challenge Persia, the Persian king initially joined the alliance against Sparta, before imposing the Peace of Antalcidas ("King's Peace") which restored Persia's control over the Anatolian Greeks.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] By 371 BC, Thebes was in the ascendancy, defeating Sparta at the Battle of Leuctra, killing the Spartan king Cleombrotus I, and invading Laconia.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Further Theban successes against Sparta in 369 led to Messenia gaining independence; Sparta never recovered from the loss of Messenia's fertile land and the helot workforce it provided.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The rising power of Thebes led Sparta and Athens to join forces; in 362 they were defeated by Thebes at the Battle of Mantinea.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the aftermath of Mantinea, none of the major Greek states were able to dominate.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Though Thebes had won the battle, their general Epaminondas was killed, and they spent the following decades embroiled in wars with their neighbours; Athens, meanwhile, saw its second naval alliance, formed in 377, collapse in the mid-350s.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The power vacuum in Greece after the Battle of Mantinea was filled by Macedon, under Philip II, starting from the battle of Crocus field.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In 338 BC, he defeated a Greek alliance at the Battle of Chaeronea, and subsequently formed the League of Corinth.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Philip planned to lead the League to invade Persia, but was murdered in 336 BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] His son Alexander the Great was left to fulfill his father's ambitions.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] After campaigns against Macedon's western and northern enemies, and those Greek states that had broken from the League of Corinth following the death of Philip, Alexander began his campaign against Persia in 334 BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] He conquered Persia, defeating Darius III at the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, and after the Battle of Gaugamela in 331 BC proclaimed himself king of Asia.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] From 329 BC he led expeditions to Bactria and then India; further plans to invade Arabia and North Africa were halted by his death in 323 BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The period from the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC until the death of Cleopatra, the last Macedonian ruler of Egypt, is known as the Hellenistic period.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the early part of this period, a new form of kingship developed based on Macedonian and Near Eastern traditions.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The first Hellenistic kings were previously Alexander's generals, and took power in the period following his death, though they were not part of existing royal lineages and lacked historic claims to the territories they controlled.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the early part of the Hellenistic period, the exact borders of the Hellenistic kingdoms were not settled.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Antigonus attempted to expand his territory by attacking the other successor kingdoms until they joined against him, and he was killed at the Battle of Ipsus in 301 BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] His son Demetrius spent many years in Seleucid captivity, and his son, Antigonus II, only reclaimed the Macedonian throne around 276.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Meanwhile, the Seleucid kingdom gave up territory in the east to the Indian king Chandragupta Maurya in exchange for war elephants, and later lost large parts of Persia to the Parthian Empire.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] By the mid-3rd century, the kingdoms of Alexander's successors was mostly stable, though there continued to be disputes over border areas.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The great capitals of Hellenistic culture were Alexandria in the Ptolemaic Kingdom and Antioch in the Seleucid Empire.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The conquests of Alexander had numerous consequences for the Greek city-states.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] It greatly widened the horizons of the Greeks and led to a steady emigration of the young and ambitious to the new Greek empires in the east.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Many Greeks migrated to Alexandria, Antioch and the many other new Hellenistic cities founded in Alexander's wake, as far away as present-day Afghanistan and Pakistan, where the Greco-Bactrian Kingdom and the Indo-Greek Kingdom survived until the end of the 1st century BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Some city-states within Greece formed themselves into two major leagues; the Achaean League (including Corinth and Argos) and the Aetolian League.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] For much of the period until the Roman conquest, these leagues were at war, often participating in the conflicts between the Diadochi's successor states to Alexander's empire.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Antigonid Kingdom became involved in a war with the Roman Republic in the late 3rd century.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Although the First Macedonian War was inconclusive, the Romans, in typical fashion, continued to fight Macedon until it was completely absorbed into the Roman Republic (by 149 BC).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the east, the unwieldy Seleucid Empire gradually disintegrated, although a rump survived until 64 BC, whilst the Ptolemaic Kingdom continued in Egypt until 30 BC when it too was conquered by the Romans.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Aetolian league grew wary of Roman involvement in Greece, and sided with the Seleucids in the Roman–Seleucid War; when the Romans were victorious, the league was effectively absorbed into the Republic.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Although the Achaean league outlasted both the Aetolian league and Macedon, it was also soon defeated and absorbed by the Romans in 146 BC, bringing Greek independence to an end.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Greek peninsula came under Roman rule during the 146 BC conquest of Greece after the Battle of Corinth.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Macedonia became a Roman province while southern Greece came under the surveillance of Macedonia's prefect; however, some Greek *poleis* managed to maintain a partial independence and avoid taxation.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Aegean Islands were added to this territory in 133 BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Athens and other Greek cities revolted in 88 BC, and the peninsula was crushed by the Roman general Sulla.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Roman civil wars devastated the land even further, until Augustus organized the peninsula as the province of Achaea in 27 BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Greece was a key eastern province of the Roman Empire, as the Roman culture had long been in fact Greco-Roman.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Greek language served as a *lingua franca* in the East and in Italy, and many Greek intellectuals such as Galen would perform most of their work in Rome.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The territory of Greece is mountainous, and as a result, ancient Greece consisted of many smaller regions, each with its own dialect, cultural peculiarities, and identity.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Regionalism and regional conflicts were prominent features of ancient Greece.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Cities tended to be located in valleys between mountains, or on coastal plains, and dominated a certain area around them.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the south lay the Peloponnese, consisting of the regions of Laconia (southeast), Messenia (southwest), Elis (west), Achaia (north), Korinthia (northeast), Argolis (east), and Arcadia (center).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] These names survive to the present day as regional units of modern Greece, though with somewhat different boundaries.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Mainland Greece to the north, nowadays known as Central Greece, consisted of Aetolia and Acarnania in the west, Locris, Doris, and Phocis in the center, while in the east lay Boeotia, Attica, and Megaris.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Northeast lay Thessaly, while Epirus lay to the northwest.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Epirus stretched from the Ambracian Gulf in the south to the Ceraunian Mountains and the Aoos river in the north, and consisted of Chaonia (north), Molossia (center), and Thesprotia (south).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the northeast corner was Macedonia, originally consisting Lower Macedonia and its regions, such as Emathia (Macedonia), Pieria, and Bottiaea, and later Almopia, Amphaxitis.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The original capital of Macedon was Aigai and then moved to Pella in the 4th century BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] To the north of Macedonia lay various non-Greek peoples such as the Paeonians due north, the Thracians to the northeast, and the Illyrians, with whom the Macedonians were frequently in conflict, to the northwest.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Chalcidice was settled early on by southern Greek colonists and was considered part of the Greek world, while from the late 2nd millennium BC substantial Greek settlement also occurred on the eastern shores of the Aegean, in Anatolia.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] This was not simply for trade, but also to found settlements.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] These Greek colonies were not, as Roman colonies were, dependent on their mother-city, but were independent city-states in their own right.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Greeks settled outside of Greece in two distinct ways.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The first was in permanent settlements founded by Greeks, which formed as independent poleis.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The second form was in what historians refer to as *emporia*; trading posts which were occupied by both Greeks and non-Greeks and which were primarily concerned with the manufacture and sale of goods.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Examples of this latter type of settlement are found at Al Mina in the east and Pithekoussai in the west.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] From around 750 to 500 BC, Greeks settled colonies in all directions.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] To the east, the Aegean coast of Asia Minor was colonized first, followed by Cyprus and the coasts of Thrace, the Sea of Marmara and the south coast of the Black Sea.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Eventually, Greek colonization reached as far northeast as present-day Ukraine and Russia (Taganrog).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] To the west the coasts of Illyria, Southern Italy (called "Magna Graecia") were settled, followed by Southern France, Corsica, and even eastern Spain.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Greek colonies were also founded in Egypt and Libya.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Modern Syracuse, Naples, Marseille and Istanbul had their beginnings as the Greek colonies Syracusae (Συράκουσαι), Neapolis (Νεάπολις), Massalia (Μασσαλία) and Byzantion (Βυζάντιον).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] These colonies played an important role in the spread of Greek influence throughout Europe and also aided in the establishment of long-distance trading networks between the Greek city-states, boosting the economy of ancient Greece.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Ancient Greece consisted of several hundred relatively independent city-states (*poleis*).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] This was a situation unlike that in most other contemporary societies, which were either tribal or kingdoms ruling over relatively large territories.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Undoubtedly, the geography of Greece—divided and sub-divided by hills, mountains, and rivers—contributed to the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] On the one hand, the ancient Greeks had no doubt that they were "one people"; they had the same religion, same basic culture, and same language.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Furthermore, the Greeks were very aware of their tribal origins; Herodotus was able to extensively categorise the city-states by tribe.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Yet, although these higher-level relationships existed, they seem to have rarely had a major role in Greek politics.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The independence of the *poleis* was fiercely defended; unification was something rarely contemplated by the ancient Greeks.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Even when, during the second Persian invasion of Greece, a group of city-states allied themselves to defend Greece, the vast majority of *poleis* remained neutral, and after the Persian defeat, the allies quickly returned to infighting.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Thus, the major peculiarities of the ancient Greek political system were its fragmented nature (and that this does not particularly seem to have tribal origin), and the particular focus on urban centers within otherwise tiny states.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The peculiarities of the Greek system are further evidenced by the colonies that they set up throughout the Mediterranean, which, though they might count a certain Greek *polis* as their 'mother' (and remain sympathetic to her), were completely independent of the founding city.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Inevitably smaller *poleis* might be dominated by larger neighbors, but conquest or direct rule by another city-state appears to have been quite rare.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Instead the *poleis* grouped themselves into leagues, membership of which was in a constant state of flux.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Later in the Classical period, the leagues would become fewer and larger, be dominated by one city (particularly Athens, Sparta and Thebes); and often *poleis* would be compelled to join under threat of war (or as part of a peace treaty).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Even after Philip II of Macedon conquered the heartlands of ancient Greece, he did not attempt to annex the territory or unify it into a new province, but compelled most of the *poleis* to join his own Corinthian League.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Initially many Greek city-states seem to have been petty kingdoms; there was often a city official carrying some residual, ceremonial functions of the king (*basileus*), e.g., the *archon basileus* in Athens.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] However, by the Archaic period and the first historical consciousness, most had already become aristocratic oligarchies.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] It is unclear exactly how this change occurred.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] For instance, in Athens, the kingship had been reduced to a hereditary, lifelong chief magistracy (*archon*) by c.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] 1050 BC; by 753 BC this had become a decennial, elected archonship, and finally an annually elected archonship by 683 BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Through each stage, more power would have been transferred to the aristocracy as a whole, and away from a single individual.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Inevitably, the domination of politics and concomitant aggregation of wealth by small groups of families was apt to cause social unrest in many *poleis*.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In many cities a tyrant (not in the modern sense of repressive autocracies), would at some point seize control and govern according to their own will; often a populist agenda would help sustain them in power.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In a system wracked with class conflict, government by a 'strongman' was often the best solution.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Athens fell under a tyranny in the second half of the 6th century BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] When this tyranny was ended, the Athenians founded the world's first democracy as a radical solution to prevent the aristocracy regaining power.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] A citizens' assembly (the *Ecclesia*), for the discussion of city policy, had existed since the reforms of Draco in 621 BC; all citizens were permitted to attend after the reforms of Solon (early 6th century), but the poorest citizens could not address the assembly or run for office.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] With the establishment of the democracy, the assembly became the *de jure* mechanism of government; all citizens had equal privileges in the assembly.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] However, non-citizens, such as metics (foreigners living in Athens) or slaves, had no political rights at all.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] After the rise of democracy in Athens, other city-states founded democracies.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] However, many retained more traditional forms of government.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] As so often in other matters, Sparta was a notable exception to the rest of Greece, ruled through the whole period by not one, but two hereditary monarchs.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Kings of Sparta belonged to the Agiads and the Eurypontids, descendants respectively of Eurysthenes and Procles.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Both dynasties' founders were believed to be twin sons of Aristodemus, a Heraclid ruler.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] However, the powers of these kings were held in check by both a council of elders (the *Gerousia*) and magistrates specifically appointed to watch over the kings (the *Ephors*).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Only free, land-owning, native-born men could be citizens entitled to the full protection of the law in a city-state.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In most city-states, unlike the situation in Rome, social prominence did not allow special rights.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Sometimes families controlled public religious functions, but this ordinarily did not give any extra power in the government.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In Athens, the population was divided into four social classes based on wealth.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] People could change classes if they made more money.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In Sparta, all male citizens were called *homoioi*, meaning "peers".
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] However, Spartan kings, who served as the city-state's dual military and religious leaders, came from two families.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Women in Ancient Greece appear to have primarily performed domestic tasks, managed households, and borne and reared children.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Slaves had the right to have a family and own property, subject to their master's goodwill and permission, but they had no political rights.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] By 600 BC, chattel slavery had spread in Greece.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] By the 5th century BC, slaves made up one-third of the total population in some city-states.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Between 40 and 80% of the population of Classical Athens were slaves.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Slaves outside of Sparta almost never revolted because they were made up of too many nationalities and were too scattered to organize.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] However, unlike later Western culture, the ancient Greeks did not think in terms of race.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Most families owned slaves as household servants and laborers, and even poor families might have owned a few slaves.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Owners were not allowed to beat or kill their slaves.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Owners often promised to free slaves in the future to encourage slaves to work hard.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Unlike in Rome, freedmen did not become citizens.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Instead, they were mixed into the population of *metics*, which included people from foreign countries or other city-states who were officially allowed to live in the state.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] These public slaves had a larger measure of independence than slaves owned by families, living on their own and performing specialized tasks.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In Athens, public slaves were trained to look out for counterfeit coinage, while temple slaves acted as servants of the temple's deity and Scythian slaves were employed in Athens as a police force corralling citizens to political functions.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Sparta had a special type of slaves called *helots*.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Helots were Messenians enslaved en masse during the Messenian Wars by the state and assigned to families where they were forced to stay.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Helots raised food and did household chores so that women could concentrate on raising strong children while men could devote their time to training as hoplites.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Their masters treated them harshly, and helots revolted against their masters several times.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In 370/369 BC, as a result of Epaminondas' liberation of Messenia from Spartan rule, the helot system there came to an end and the helots won their freedom.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] However, it persisted in Laconia until the 2nd century BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] For most of Greek history, education was private, except in Sparta.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] During the Hellenistic period, some city-states established public schools.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Only wealthy families could afford a teacher.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Boys learned how to read, write and quote literature.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] They also learned to sing and play one musical instrument and were trained as athletes for military service.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] They studied not for a job but to become an effective citizen.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Girls also learned to read, write and do simple arithmetic so they could manage the household.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] They almost never received education after childhood.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Boys went to school at the age of seven, or went to the barracks, if they lived in Sparta.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The three types of teachings were: grammatistes for arithmetic, kitharistes for music and dancing, and Paedotribae for sports.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Boys from wealthy families attending the private school lessons were taken care of by a *paidagogos*, a household slave selected for this task who accompanied the boy during the day.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Classes were held in teachers' private houses and included reading, writing, mathematics, singing, and playing the lyre and flute.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] When the boy became 12 years old the schooling started to include sports such as wrestling, running, and throwing discus and javelin.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In Athens, some older youths attended academy for the finer disciplines such as culture, sciences, music, and the arts.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The schooling ended at age 18, followed by military training in the army usually for one or two years.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Some of Athens' greatest such schools included the Lyceum (the so-called Peripatetic school founded by Aristotle of Stageira) and the Platonic Academy (founded by Plato of Athens).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The education system of the wealthy ancient Greeks is also called Paideia.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] At its economic height in the 5th and 4th centuries BC, the free citizenry of Classical Greece represented perhaps the most prosperous society in the ancient world, some economic historians considering Greece one of the most advanced pre-industrial economies.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In terms of wheat, wages reached an estimated 7–12 kg (15–26 lb) daily for an unskilled worker in urban Athens, 2–3 times the 3.75 kg (8.3 lb) of an unskilled rural labourer in Roman Egypt, though Greek farm incomes too were on average lower than those available to urban workers.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] At least in the Archaic period, the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece, with many competing city-states, increased the frequency of conflict but conversely limited the scale of warfare.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Unable to maintain professional armies, the city-states relied on their own citizens to fight.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] This inevitably reduced the potential duration of campaigns, as citizens would need to return to their own professions (especially in the case of, for example, farmers).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Campaigns would therefore often be restricted to summer.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] When battles occurred, they were usually set piece and intended to be decisive.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Casualties were slight compared to later battles, rarely amounting to more than five percent of the losing side, but the slain often included the most prominent citizens and generals who led from the front.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The scale and scope of warfare in ancient Greece changed dramatically as a result of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] To fight the enormous armies of the Achaemenid Empire was effectively beyond the capabilities of a single city-state.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The eventual triumph of the Greeks was achieved by alliances of city-states (the exact composition changing over time), allowing the pooling of resources and division of labor.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Although alliances between city-states occurred before this time, nothing on this scale had been seen before.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The rise of Athens and Sparta as pre-eminent powers during this conflict led directly to the Peloponnesian War, which saw further development of the nature of warfare, strategy and tactics.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Fought between leagues of cities dominated by Athens and Sparta, the increased manpower and financial resources increased the scale and allowed the diversification of warfare.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Set-piece battles during the Peloponnesian war proved indecisive and instead there was increased reliance on attritionary strategies, naval battles and blockades and sieges.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] These changes greatly increased the number of casualties and the disruption of Greek society.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Athens owned one of the largest war fleets in ancient Greece.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] It had over 200 triremes each powered by 170 oarsmen who were seated in 3 rows on each side of the ship.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The city could afford such a large fleet—it had over 34,000 oarsmen—because it owned a lot of silver mines that were worked by slaves.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] According to Josiah Ober, Greek city-states faced approximately a one-in-three chance of destruction during the archaic and classical period.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek philosophy focused on the role of reason and inquiry.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In many ways, it had an important influence on modern philosophy, as well as modern science.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Clear unbroken lines of influence lead from ancient Greek and Hellenistic philosophers, to medieval Muslim philosophers and Islamic scientists, to the European Renaissance and Enlightenment, to the secular sciences of the modern day.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Neither reason nor inquiry began with the ancient Greeks.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Defining the difference between the Greek quest for knowledge and the quests of the elder civilizations, such as the ancient Egyptians and Babylonians, has long been a topic of study by theorists of civilization.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The first known philosophers of Greece were the pre-Socratics, who attempted to provide naturalistic, non-mythical descriptions of the world.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] They were followed by Socrates, one of the first philosophers based in Athens during its golden age whose ideas, despite being known by second-hand accounts instead of writings of his own, laid the basis of Western philosophy.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Socrates' disciple Plato, who wrote *The Republic* and established a radical difference between ideas and the concrete world, and Plato's disciple Aristotle, who wrote extensively about nature and ethics, are also immensely influential in Western philosophy to this day.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The later Hellenistic philosophy, also originating in Greece, is defined by names such as Antisthenes (cynicism), Zeno of Citium (stoicism) and Plotinus (Neoplatonism).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek literature was poetry and was composed for performance rather than private consumption.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek poet known is Homer, although he was certainly part of an existing tradition of oral poetry.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Homer's poetry, though it was developed around the same time that the Greeks developed writing, would have been composed orally; the first poet to certainly compose their work in writing was Archilochus, a lyric poet from the mid-7th century BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Tragedy developed around the end of the archaic period, taking elements from across the pre-existing genres of late archaic poetry.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Like poetry, Greek prose had its origins in the archaic period, and the earliest writers of Greek philosophy, history, and medical literature all date to the 6th century BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Prose first emerged as the writing style adopted by the presocratic philosophers Anaximander and Anaximenes—though Thales of Miletus, considered the first Greek philosopher, apparently wrote nothing.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Prose as a genre reached maturity in the classical era, and the major Greek prose genres—philosophy, history, rhetoric, and dialogue—developed in this period.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period saw the literary centre of the Greek world move from Athens, where it had been in the classical period, to Alexandria.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] At the same time, other Hellenistic kings such as the Antigonids and the Attalids were patrons of scholarship and literature, turning Pella and Pergamon respectively into cultural centres.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] It was thanks to this cultural patronage by Hellenistic kings, and especially the Museum at Alexandria, that so much ancient Greek literature has survived.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Library of Alexandria, part of the Museum, had the previously unenvisaged aim of collecting together copies of all known authors in Greek.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Almost all of the surviving non-technical Hellenistic literature is poetry, and Hellenistic poetry tended to be highly intellectual, blending different genres and traditions, and avoiding linear narratives.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period also saw a shift in the ways literature was consumed—while in the archaic and classical periods literature had typically been experienced in public performance, in the Hellenistic period it was more commonly read privately.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] At the same time, Hellenistic poets began to write for private, rather than public, consumption.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] With Octavian's victory at Actium in 31 BC, Rome began to become a major centre of Greek literature, as important Greek authors such as Strabo and Dionysius of Halicarnassus came to Rome.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The period of greatest innovation in Greek literature under Rome was the "long second century" from approximately 80 AD to around 230 AD.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] This innovation was especially marked in prose, with the development of the novel and a revival of prominence for display oratory both dating to this period.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In Ancient Greek society, music was ever-present and considered a fundamental component of civilisation.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] It was an important part of public religious worship, private ceremonies such as weddings and funerals, and household entertainment.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Men sang and played music at the symposium; both men and women sang at work; and children's games involved song and dance.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek music was primarily vocal, sung either by a solo singer or a chorus, and usually accompanied by an instrument; purely instrumental music was less common.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Greeks used stringed instruments, including lyres, harps, and lutes; and wind instruments, of which the most important was the *aulos*, a reed instrument.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Percussion instruments played a relatively unimportant role supporting stringed and wind instruments, and were used in certain religious cults.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek mathematics contributed many important developments to mathematics, including the basic rules of geometry, the idea of formal mathematical proof, and discoveries in number theory, mathematical analysis, applied mathematics, and approached close to establishing integral calculus.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The discoveries of several Greek mathematicians, including Pythagoras, Euclid, and Archimedes, are still used in mathematical teaching today.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Greeks developed astronomy, which they treated as a branch of mathematics, to a highly sophisticated level.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The first geometrical, three-dimensional models to explain the apparent motion of the planets were developed in the 4th century BC by Eudoxus of Cnidus and Callippus of Cyzicus.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Their younger contemporary Heraclides Ponticus proposed that the Earth rotates around its axis.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the 3rd century BC, Aristarchus of Samos was the first to suggest a heliocentric system.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Archimedes in his treatise The Sand Reckoner revives Aristarchus' hypothesis that *"the fixed stars and the Sun remain unmoved, while the Earth revolves about the Sun on the circumference of a circle"*.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Otherwise, only fragmentary descriptions of Aristarchus' idea survive.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Eratosthenes, using the angles of shadows created at widely separated regions, estimated the circumference of the Earth with great accuracy.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the 2nd century BC Hipparchus of Nicea made a number of contributions, including the first measurement of precession and the compilation of the first star catalog in which he proposed the modern system of apparent magnitudes.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Antikythera mechanism, a device for calculating the movements of planets, dates from about 80 BC and was the first ancestor of the astronomical computer.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] It was discovered in an ancient shipwreck off the Greek island of Antikythera, between Kythera and Crete.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The device became famous for its use of a differential gear, previously believed to have been invented in the 16th century, and the miniaturization and complexity of its parts, comparable to a clock made in the 18th century.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The original mechanism is displayed in the Bronze collection of the National Archaeological Museum of Athens, accompanied by a replica.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The ancient Greeks also made important discoveries in the medical field.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Hippocrates was a physician of the Classical period, and is considered one of the most outstanding figures in the history of medicine.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] He is referred to as the "father of medicine" in recognition of his lasting contributions to the field as the founder of the Hippocratic school of medicine.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] This intellectual school revolutionized medicine in ancient Greece, establishing it as a discipline distinct from other fields that it had traditionally been associated with (notably theurgy and philosophy), thus making medicine a profession.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The art of ancient Greece has exercised an enormous influence on the culture of many countries from ancient times to the present day, particularly in the areas of sculpture and architecture.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the West, the art of the Roman Empire was largely derived from Greek models.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] In the East, Alexander the Great's conquests initiated several centuries of exchange between Greek, Central Asian and Indian cultures, resulting in Greco-Buddhist art, with ramifications as far as Japan.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Following the Renaissance in Europe, the humanist aesthetic and the high technical standards of Greek art inspired generations of European artists.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Well into the 19th century, the classical tradition derived from Greece dominated the art of the Western world.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Religion was a central part of ancient Greek life.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Though the Greeks of different cities and tribes worshipped similar gods, religious practices were not uniform and the gods were thought of differently in different places.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The Greeks were polytheistic, worshipping many gods, but as early as the 6th century BC a pantheon of twelve Olympians began to develop.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Greek religion was influenced by the practices of the Greeks' near eastern neighbours at least as early as the archaic period, and by the Hellenistic period this influence was seen in both directions.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The most important religious act in ancient Greece was animal sacrifice, most commonly of sheep and goats.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Sacrifice was accompanied by public prayer, and prayer and hymns were themselves a major part of ancient Greek religious life.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] The civilization of ancient Greece has been immensely influential on language, politics, educational systems, philosophy, science, and the arts.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] It became the *Leitkultur* of the Roman Empire to the point of marginalizing native Italic traditions.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] Via the Roman Empire, Greek culture came to be foundational to Western culture in general.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greece] A modern revival of Classical Greek learning took place in the Neoclassicism movement in 18th- and 19th-century Europe and the Americas.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] There are also several historical forms.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:archias-of-pella/ancient-greek] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Arrian was born in Nicomedia (present-day İzmit), the provincial capital of Bithynia.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Cassius Dio called him Flavius Arrianus Nicomediensis.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Sources provide similar dates for his birth, within a few years prior to 90, 89, and 85–90 AD.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The line of reasoning for dates belonging to 85–90 AD is because of Arrian being made a consul around 130 AD, and the usual age for this, during this period, being 42 years of age.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] His family was from the Greek provincial aristocracy, and his full name, *L.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Flavius Arrianus*, indicates that he was a Roman citizen, suggesting that the citizenship went back several generations, probably to the time of the Roman conquest some 170 years before.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Sometime during the second century AD (117 to 120 AD) while in Epirus, probably Nicopolis, Arrian attended lectures of Epictetus of Nicopolis, and proceeded within a time to fall into his pupillage, a fact attested to by Lucian.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] All that is known about the life of Epictetus is due to Arrian, in that Arrian left an *Encheiridion* (*Handbook*) of Epictetus' philosophy.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] After Epirus, he went to Athens, and while there, he became known as the "young Xenophon" as a consequence of the similarity of his relationship to Epictetus as Xenophon had to Socrates.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] For a period, some time about 126 AD, he was a friend of the emperor Hadrian's, who appointed him to the Senate.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] He was appointed to the position *consul suffectus* around 130 AD, and then, in 132 AD (although Howatson shows 131), he was made prefect or legate (governor) of Cappadocia by Hadrian, a service he continued for six years.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Historian Cassius Dio states that not long after the Bar Kokhba revolt in Judea had been quelled, in 135 AD, King Pharasmanes II of Iberia caused the Alani to invade neighbouring territories, including Cappadocia, where their advance was robustly halted by Arrian's legions.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Arrian referred to himself as "the second Xenophon", on account of his reputation and the esteem in which he was held.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] This quality is identified as *paideia* (παιδεία), which is the quality considered to be of one who is known as an educated and learned personage, i.e., one who is highly esteemed and important.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The *Indica* and the *Anabasis* are the only works completely intact.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] His entire remaining *oeuvre* is known as *FGrH 156* to designate those collected fragments that exist.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] This work is the earliest extant work that is dated with any confidence.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] It is a writing addressed to Emperor Hadrian.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Arrian was a pupil of Epictetus around 108 AD, and, according to his own account, he was moved to publish his notes of Epictetus' lectures, which are known as *Discourses of Epictetus*, by their unauthorized dissemination.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] According to George Long, Arrian noted from Epictetus' lectures for his private use and some time later made of these, the *Discourses*.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Photius states that Arrian produced two books the *Dissertations* and the *Discourses*.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The Discourses are also known as *Diatribai* and are apparently a verbatim recording of Epictetus' lectures.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The *Enchiridion* is a short compendium of all Epictetus' philosophical principles.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] It is also known as a handbook, and A Mehl considers the *Enchiridion* to have been a *vade mecum* for Arrian.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The *Enchiridion* is apparently a summary of the Discourses.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] JB Stockdale considered that Arrian wrote eight books of which four were lost by the Middle Ages and the remaining ones became the *Discourses*.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] In a comparison of the contents of the *Enchiridion* with the *Discourses*, it is apparent that the former contains material not present within the latter, suggesting an original lost source for the *Enchiridion*.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The *Anabasis of Alexander* comprises seven books.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Arrian used Xenophon's account of the March of Cyrus as the basis for this work.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Three extant fragments are the *Vatican Palimpsest* (of the 10th century AD), PSI 12.1284 (Oxyrhynchus), and the *Gothenburg palimpsest* (of the 10th century also), these possibly stemming originally from Photius.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The writing is about the successors of Alexander the Great, circa 323 – 321 or 319.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] A lost work of seventeen books, fragments of *Parthica* were maintained by the Suda and Stephanus of Byzantium.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The work survives only in adaptations made later by Photius and Syncellus.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Translated, the title is *History of the Parthians*.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Arrian's aim in the work was to set forth events of the Parthian war of Trajan.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The writing mentioned that the Parthians trace their origins to Artaxerxes II.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] A work of eight books, *Bibliotheca* (via Photius) states it is the fourth to have been written by Arrian.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Written 136/137 AD (in the 20th year of Hadrian), *Techne Taktike* ('the art/craft of tactics') is a treatise on Roman cavalry and military tactics, and includes information on the nature, arms and discipline of the phalanx.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The *hippika gymnasia* is a particular concern of Arrian in the treatise.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Another translation of the title is *Ars tactica*, which, in Greek, is Τέχνη τακτική.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] This work has generally been considered in large part a panegyric to Hadrian, written for the occasion of his *vīcennālia*, although some scholars have argued that its second half may have had practical use.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The work was inspired by and designed as an addition to an earlier exposition made by Xenophon, whom Arrian recognised to be the Ancient Greek authority on the subject of hunting with scent hounds.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Within the work, Arrian explicitly identified the particular means of pursuing warfare as being based on Greek methods.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] There were also a number of monographs or biographies, including of Dion of Syracuse, Timoleon of Corinth, and Tilliborus, a brigand or robber of Asia Minor, which are now lost.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Everything known of his life derives from the 9th century writing of Photius in his *Bibliotheca*, and from those few references which exist within Arrian's own writings.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The knowledge of his consulship, is derived at the least from literature produced by Suidas.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Arrian was also known of by Aulus Gellius.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Pliny the Younger addressed seven of his epistles to him.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Simplicius made a copy of the Enchiridion, which was transmitted under the name of the monastic father Nilus during the 5th century, and as a result found in every monastery library.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Nicholas Blancard made translations of Arrian in 1663 and 1668.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The voyage of Nearchus and *Periplus of the Erythrean Sea* were translated from the Greek by the then Dean of Westminster, William Vincent, and published in 1809.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Vincent published a commentary in 1797 on *The voyage of Nearchus*.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] The work was also translated into French by M.
[src:archias-of-pella/arrian] Billecocq, under the auspices of the government (cf. p.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The area that straddles the present-day territory of Bahrain was once the site of the ancient Dilmun civilisation.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] It has been famed since antiquity for its pearl fisheries, which were considered the best in the world into the 19th century.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain was one of the earliest areas to be influenced by Islam, during the lifetime of Muhammad in 628.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Following a period of Arab rule, Bahrain was ruled by the Portuguese Empire from 1521 until 1602, when they were expelled by Shah Abbas the Great of the Safavid Iran.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1783, the Bani Utbah and allied tribes captured Bahrain from Nasr Al-Madhkur.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] It has since been ruled by the Al Khalifa royal family, with Ahmed al Fateh as Bahrain's first *hakim*.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In the late 19th century, following successive treaties with the British, Bahrain became a protectorate of the United Kingdom.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Formerly an emirate, Bahrain was declared a semi-constitutional monarchy in 2002, and Article 2 of the constitution made sharia a principal source for legislation.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 2011, the country experienced protests inspired by the regional Arab Spring.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The ruling Sunni Muslim Al Khalifa royal family has been criticised for violating the human rights of groups including dissidents, political opposition figures, and its Shia Muslim population.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain is known as one of the first post-oil economies in the Persian Gulf, the result of decades of investing in the banking and tourism sectors.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Many of the world's largest financial institutions have a presence in Manama, but oil revenues still constitute a significant part of its government budget.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] It is recognised by the World Bank as a high-income economy.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain is a member of the United Nations, the Non-Aligned Movement, the Arab League, the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation, and the Gulf Cooperation Council.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] It is a Dialogue partner of the Shanghai Cooperation Organization.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] It remains disputed which "two seas" the name *Bahrayn* originally refers to.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The term appears five times in the Quran but does not refer to the modern island—originally known to the Arabs as *Awal*.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Today, Bahrain's "two seas" are generally taken to be the bay east and west of the island, the seas north and south of the island, or the salt and fresh water present above and below the ground.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In addition to wells, there are areas of the sea north of Bahrain where fresh water bubbles up in the middle of the saltwater as noted by visitors since antiquity.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] An alternative theory concerning Bahrain's toponymy is offered by the al-Ahsa region, which suggests that the two seas were the "Great Green Ocean" (the Persian Gulf) and Al-Asfar Lake on the Arabian mainland.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Until the late Middle Ages, "Bahrain" referred to the region of Eastern Arabia that included southern Iraq, Kuwait, Al-Hasa, Qatif, and Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The region stretched from Basra in Iraq to the Strait of Hormuz in Oman.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] This was Iqlīm al-Bahrayn's "Bahrayn Province".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] When the term "Bahrain" began to refer solely to the Awal archipelago is unknown.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The entire coastal strip of Eastern Arabia was known as "Bahrain" for a millennium.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The island and kingdom were also commonly spelled **Bahrein**.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain was home to Dilmun, an important Bronze Age trade centre linking Mesopotamia and the Indus Valley.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain was later ruled by the Sumerians and Babylonians.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] From the 6th to 3rd century BC, Bahrain was part of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] By about 250 BC, Parthia brought the Persian Gulf under its control and extended its influence as far as Oman.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The Parthians established garrisons along the southern coast of the Persian Gulf to control trade routes.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] During the classical era, Bahrain was referred to by the ancient Greeks as *Tylos*, the centre of pearl trading, when the Greek admiral Nearchus serving under Alexander landed on Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The Greek philosopher and a botanist Theophrastus states that much of Bahrain was covered by these cotton trees and that Bahrain was famous for exporting walking canes engraved with emblems that were customarily carried in Babylon.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Alexander had planned to settle Greek colonists in Bahrain, and although it is not clear that this happened on the scale he envisaged, Bahrain became very much part of the Hellenised world: the language of the upper classes was Greek, with Aramaic in everyday use.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Local coinage shows a seated Zeus, who may have been worshipped there as a syncretised form of the Arabian sun-god Shams.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Tylos was also the site of Greek athletic contests.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The Greek historian Strabo believed the Phoenicians originated from Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Herodotus also believed that the homeland of the Phoenicians was Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] However, there is little evidence of any human settlement at all on Bahrain during the time when such migration had supposedly taken place.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The name Tylos is thought to be a Hellenisation of the Semitic *Tilmun* (from Dilmun).
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The term Tylos was commonly used for the islands until Ptolemy's *Geographia* when the inhabitants are referred to as Thilouanoi.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Some place names in Bahrain go back to the Tylos era; for instance the name of Arad, a residential suburb of Muharraq, is believed to originate from "Arados", the ancient Greek name for Muharraq.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In the 3rd century, Ardashir I, the first ruler of the Sassanid dynasty, marched on Oman and Bahrain, where he defeated Sanatruq the ruler of Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain was the site of worship of an ox deity called Awal (Arabic: اوال).
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Worshipers built a large statue to Awal in Muharraq, although it has now been lost.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] For many centuries after *Tylos*, Bahrain was known as *Awal*.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] By the 5th century, Bahrain became a centre for Nestorian Christianity, with the village Samahij as the seat of bishops.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 410, according to the Oriental Syriac Church synodal records, a bishop named Batai was excommunicated from the church in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] As a sect, the Nestorians were often persecuted as heretics by the Byzantine Empire, but Bahrain was outside the empire's control, offering some safety.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The names of several Muharraq villages today reflect Bahrain's Christian legacy, with Al Dair meaning "the monastery".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain's pre-Muslim population consisted of Christian Arabs (mostly Abd al-Qays), Persians (Zoroastrians), Jews, and Aramaic-speaking agriculturalists.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] According to Robert Bertram Serjeant, the Baharna may be the Arabised "descendants of converts from the original population of Christians (Aramaeans), Jews and Persians inhabiting the island and cultivated coastal provinces of Eastern Arabia at the time of the Muslim conquest".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The sedentary people of pre-Muslim Bahrain were Aramaic speakers and to some degree Persian speakers, while Syriac functioned as a liturgical language.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Muhammad's first interaction with the people of Bahrain was the Al Kudr Invasion.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Muhammad ordered a surprise attack on the Banu Salim tribe for plotting to attack Medina.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] He had received news that some tribes were assembling an army in Bahrain and preparing to attack the mainland, but the tribesmen retreated when they learned Muhammad was leading an army to do battle with them.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Traditional Muslim accounts state that Al-Ala'a Al-Hadrami was sent as an envoy during the Expedition of Zayd ibn Harithah (Hisma) to the Bahrain region by Muhammad in AD 628 and that Munzir ibn Sawa Al Tamimi, the local ruler, responded to his mission and converted the entire area.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 899, the Qarmatians, a millenarian Ismaili Muslim sect, seized Bahrain, seeking to create a utopian society based on reason and redistribution of property among initiates.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Thereafter, the Qarmatians demanded tribute from the caliph in Baghdad, and in 930 sacked Mecca, bringing the sacred Black Stone back to their base in Ahsa, in medieval Bahrain, for ransom.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] According to historian Al-Juwayni, the stone was returned 22 years later in 951 under mysterious circumstances.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Wrapped in a sack, it was thrown into the Great Mosque of Kufa in Iraq, accompanied by a note saying "By command we took it, and by command, we have brought it back." The theft and removal of the Black Stone caused it to break into seven pieces.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Following their defeat in 976 by the Abbasids, the Qarmatians were overthrown by the Arab Uyunid dynasty of al-Hasa, who took over the entire Bahrain region in 1076.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The Uyunids controlled Bahrain until 1235, when the archipelago was briefly occupied by the Persian ruler of Fars.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1253, the Usfurids brought down the Uyunid dynasty, thereby gaining control over eastern Arabia, including the islands of Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1330, the archipelago became a tributary state of the rulers of Hormuz.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Locally, the islands were controlled by the Shia Jarwanid dynasty of Qatif.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In the mid-15th century, the archipelago came under the rule of the Jabrids, a Bedouin dynasty also based in Al-Ahsa that ruled most of eastern Arabia.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1521, the Portuguese allied with Hormuz and seized Bahrain from the Jabrid ruler Muqrin ibn Zamil, who was killed during the takeover.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Portuguese rule lasted for around 80 years, during which time they depended mainly on Sunni Persian governors.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The Portuguese were expelled from the islands in 1602 by Abbas I of the Safavid Iran, which gave impetus to Shia Islam.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] For the next two centuries, Persian rulers retained control of the archipelago, interrupted by the 1717 and 1738 invasions of the Ibadis of Oman.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] During most of this period, they resorted to governing Bahrain indirectly, either through the city of Bushehr or through immigrant Sunni Arab clans.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The latter were tribes returning to the Arabian side of the Persian Gulf from Persian territories in the north who were known as *Huwala*.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1753, the Huwala clan of Nasr Al-Madhkur invaded Bahrain on behalf of the Iranian Zand leader Karim Khan Zand and restored direct Iranian rule.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1783, Al-Madhkur lost the islands of Bahrain following his defeat by the Bani Utbah clan and allied tribes at the 1782 Battle of Zubarah.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain was not new territory to the Bani Utbah; they had been a presence there since the 17th century.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] During that time, they started purchasing date palm gardens in Bahrain; a document shows that 81 years before the arrival of the Al Khalifa, one of the sheikhs of the Al Bin Ali tribe (an offshoot of the Bani Utbah) had bought a palm garden from Mariam bint Ahmed Al Sanadi in Sitra island.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The Al Bin Ali were the dominant group controlling the town of Zubarah on the Qatar peninsula, originally the centre of power of the Bani Utbah.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] After the Bani Utbah gained control of Bahrain, the Al Bin Ali had a practically independent status there as a self-governing tribe.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] They used a flag with four red and three white stripes, called the Al-Sulami flag in Bahrain, Qatar, Kuwait, and the Eastern province of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Later, different Arab family clans and tribes from Qatar moved to Bahrain to settle after the fall of Nasr Al-Madhkur of Bushehr.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] These families included the House of Khalifa, Al-Ma'awdah, Al-Buainain, Al-Fadhil, Al-Kuwari, Al-Mannai, Al-Noaimi, Al-Rumaihi, Al-Sulaiti, Al-Sadah, Al-Thawadi and other families and tribes.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The House of Khalifa moved from Qatar to Bahrain in 1799.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Originally, their ancestors were expelled from Umm Qasr in central Arabia by the Ottomans due to their predatory habits of preying on caravans in Basra and trading ships in Shatt al-Arab waterway until Turks expelled them to Kuwait in 1716, where they remained until 1766.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Around the 1760s, the Al Jalahma and House of Khalifa, both belonging to the Utub Federation, migrated to Zubarah in modern-day Qatar, leaving Al Sabah as the sole proprietors of Kuwait.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In the early 19th century, Bahrain was invaded by both the Omanis and the Al Sauds.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1802 it was governed by a 12-year-old child, when the Omani ruler Sayyid Sultan installed his son, Salim, as governor in the Arad Fort.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1816, the British political resident in the Persian Gulf, William Bruce, received a letter from the Sheikh of Bahrain who was concerned about a rumour that Britain would support an attack on the island by the Imam of Muscat.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] He sailed to Bahrain to reassure the Sheikh that this was not the case and drew up an informal agreement assuring the Sheikh that Britain would remain a neutral party.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1820, the Al Khalifa tribe were recognised by the United Kingdom as the rulers ("Al-Hakim" in Arabic) of Bahrain after signing a treaty relationship.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] However, ten years later they were forced to pay yearly tributes to Egypt despite seeking Persian and British protection.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1860, the Al Khalifas used the same tactic when the British tried to overpower Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Writing letters to the Persians and Ottomans, Al Khalifas agreed to place Bahrain under the latter's protection in March due to offering better conditions.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Eventually, the Government of British India overpowered Bahrain when the Persians refused to protect it.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Colonel Pelly signed a new treaty with Al Khalifas placing Bahrain under British rule and protection.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Following the Qatari–Bahraini War in 1868, British representatives signed another agreement with the Al Khalifas.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] It specified that the ruler could not dispose of any of his territories except to the United Kingdom and could not enter into relationships with any foreign government without British consent.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In return the British promised to protect Bahrain from all aggression by sea and to lend support in case of land attack.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] More importantly the British promised to support the rule of the Al Khalifa in Bahrain, securing its unstable position as rulers of the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Other agreements in 1880 and 1892 sealed the protectorate status of Bahrain to the British.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Unrest amongst the people of Bahrain began when Britain officially established complete dominance over the territory in 1892.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The first revolt and widespread uprising took place in March 1895 against Sheikh Issa bin Ali, then ruler of Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Sheikh Issa was the first of the Al Khalifa to rule without Persian relations.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Sir Arnold Wilson, Britain's representative in the Persian Gulf and author of *The Persian Gulf*, arrived in Bahrain from Muscat at this time.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The uprising developed further with some protesters killed by British forces.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Before the development of the petroleum industry, the island was largely devoted to pearl fisheries and, as late as the 19th century, was considered to be the finest in the world.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1903, German explorer Hermann Burchardt visited Bahrain and took many photographs of historical sites, including the old *Qaṣr es-Sheikh*, photos now stored at the Ethnological Museum of Berlin.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Before the First World War, there were about 400 vessels hunting pearls and an annual export of more than £30,000.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1911, a group of Bahraini merchants demanded restrictions on the British influence in the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The group's leaders were subsequently arrested and exiled to India.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1923, the British introduced administrative reforms and replaced Sheikh Issa bin Ali with his son.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Some clerical opponents and families, such as Al Dosari, left or were exiled to Saudi Arabia.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Three years later the British placed the country under the *de facto* rule of Charles Belgrave who operated as an adviser to the ruler until 1957.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Belgrave brought a number of reforms such as establishment of the country's first modern school in 1919 and the abolition of slavery in 1937.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] At the same time, the pearl diving industry developed at a rapid pace.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1927, Rezā Shāh, then Shah of Iran, demanded sovereignty over Bahrain in a letter to the League of Nations, a move that prompted Belgrave to undertake harsh measures including encouraging conflicts between Shia and Sunni Muslims to bring down the uprisings and limit the Iranian influence.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Belgrave even went further by suggesting to rename the Persian Gulf to the "Arabian Gulf"; however, the proposal was refused by the British government.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Britain's interest in Bahrain's development was motivated by concerns over Saudi and Iranian ambitions in the region.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The Bahrain Petroleum Company (Bapco), a subsidiary of the Standard Oil Company of California (Socal), discovered oil in 1932.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In the early 1930s, Bahrain Airport was developed.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Imperial Airways flew there, including the Handley Page HP42 aircraft.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Later in the same decade, the Bahrain Maritime Airport was established, for flying boats and seaplanes.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain participated in the Second World War on the Allied side, joining on 10 September 1939.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] On 19 October 1940, four Italian SM.82s bombers bombed Bahrain alongside Dhahran oilfields in Saudi Arabia, attacking Allied-operated oil refineries.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Although minimal damage was caused in both locations, the attack forced the Allies to upgrade Bahrain's defences, an action which further stretched Allied military resources.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] After World War II, increasing sentiments against British occupation spread throughout Arab countries and led to protests in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The protests focused on the Jewish community.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1948, following rising hostilities and looting, most members of Bahrain's Jewish community abandoned their properties and fled to Bombay, later settling in Israel (Pardes Hanna-Karkur) and the United Kingdom.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] As of 2008, 37 Jews remained in the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In the 1950s, the National Union Committee, formed by reformists following sectarian clashes, demanded an elected popular assembly, removal of Belgrave and carried out a number of protests and general strikes.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1965 a month-long uprising broke out after hundreds of workers at the Bahrain Petroleum Company were laid off.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] On 15 August 1971, though the Shah of Iran was claiming historical sovereignty over Bahrain, he accepted a referendum held by the United Nations and eventually Bahrain declared independence and signed a new treaty of friendship with Britain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain joined the United Nations and the Arab League later in the year.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The oil boom of the 1970s benefited Bahrain greatly, although the subsequent downturn hurt the economy.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The country had already begun diversification of its economy and benefited further from the Lebanese Civil War in the 1970s and 1980s, when Bahrain replaced Beirut as the Middle East's financial hub after Lebanon's large banking sector was driven out of the country by the war.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 1981, following the 1979 revolution in Iran, the Bahraini Shia population orchestrated a failed coup attempt under the auspices of a front organisation, the Islamic Front for the Liberation of Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The coup would have installed a Shia cleric exiled in Iran, Hujjatu l-Islām Hādī al-Mudarrisī, as supreme leader heading a theocratic government.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In December 1994, a group of youths threw stones at female runners for running bare-legged during an international marathon.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The resulting clash with police soon grew into civil unrest.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] A popular uprising occurred between 1994 and 2000 in which leftists, liberals and fundamentalists joined forces.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The event resulted in approximately forty deaths and ended after Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa became the Emir of Bahrain in 1999.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] He instituted elections for parliament, gave women the right to vote, and released all political prisoners.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] A referendum on 14–15 February 2001 massively supported the National Action Charter.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] As part of the adoption of the National Action Charter on 14 February 2002, Bahrain changed its formal name from the State (*dawla*) of Bahrain to the Kingdom of Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] At the same time, the title of the Head of State, Hamad bin Isa al-Khalifa, was changed from Emir to King.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The country participated in military action against the Taliban in October 2001 by deploying a frigate in the Arabian Sea for rescue and humanitarian operations.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] As a result, in November of that year, American president George W.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bush's administration designated Bahrain as a "major non-NATO ally".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain opposed the 2003 American-led invasion of Iraq and had offered Saddam Hussein asylum in the days before the invasion.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Relations improved with neighbouring Qatar after the border dispute over the Hawar Islands was resolved by the International Court of Justice in The Hague in 2001.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Following the political liberalisation of the country, Bahrain negotiated a free trade agreement with America in 2004.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 2005, Qal'at al-Bahrain, a fort and archaeological complex was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Inspired by the regional Arab Spring, Bahrain's Shia population started large protests against its Sunni rulers in early 2011.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The government initially allowed protests following a pre-dawn raid on protesters camped in Pearl Roundabout.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] A month later it requested security assistance from Saudi Arabia and other Gulf Cooperation Council countries and declared a three-month state of emergency.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The government then launched a crackdown on the opposition that included conducting thousands of arrests and systematic torture.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Almost daily clashes between protesters and security forces led to dozens of deaths.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Protests, sometimes staged by opposition parties, were ongoing.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] More than 80 civilians and 13 policemen have been killed as of March 2014.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] According to Physicians for Human Rights, 34 of these deaths were related to government usage of tear gas originally manufactured by America-based Federal Laboratories.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The lack of coverage by Arab media in the Persian Gulf, as compared to other Arab Spring uprisings, has sparked several controversies.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain remains militarily and financially dependent on Saudi Arabia and the UAE, though this is changing with the economic reforms being implemented by the government.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] On 28 February 2026, the United States and Israel launched joint airstrikes on Iran, killing the supreme leader of Iran and many other Iranian officials, starting a war with the stated goal of regime change.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Iran responded with missile and drone strikes against Israel and US bases and US allies in the region, including Bahrain, which suffered material and civilian casualties.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain is a generally flat and arid archipelago in the Persian Gulf.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] It consists of a low desert plain rising gently to a low central escarpment with the highest point the 134 m (440 ft) Mountain of Smoke *(Jabal ad Dukhan)*.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain had a total area of 665 km2 (257 sq mi) but due to land reclamation, the area increased to 780 km2 (300 sq mi).
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Often described as an archipelago of 33 islands, extensive land reclamation projects have changed this; by August 2008 the number of islands and island groups had increased to 84.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain does not share a land boundary with another country but does have a 161 km (100 mi) coastline.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The country also claims a further 22 km (12 nmi) of territorial sea and a 44 km (24 nmi) contiguous zone.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain's largest islands are Bahrain Island, the Hawar Islands, Muharraq Island, Umm an Nasan, and Sitra.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain has mild winters and very hot, humid summers.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The country's natural resources include large quantities of oil and natural gas as well as fish in the offshore waters.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Arable land constitutes only 2.82% of the total area.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] About 92% of Bahrain is desert with periodic droughts and dust storms, the main natural hazards for Bahrainis.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In Bahrain forest cover is around 1% of the total land area, equivalent to 700 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, up from 220 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] For the year 2015, 100% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The agricultural and domestic sectors' over-utilisation of the Dammam Aquifer, the principal aquifer in Bahrain, has led to its salinisation by adjacent brackish and saline water bodies.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] A hydrochemical study identified the locations of the sources of aquifer salinisation and delineated their areas of influence.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The investigation indicates that the aquifer water quality is significantly modified as groundwater flows from the northwestern parts of Bahrain, where the aquifer receives its water by lateral underflow from eastern Saudi Arabia to the southern and southeastern parts.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Four alternatives for the management of groundwater quality that are available to the water authorities in Bahrain are discussed and their priority areas are proposed, based on the type and extent of each salinisation source, in addition to groundwater use in that area.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The Zagros Mountains across the Persian Gulf in Iran cause low-level winds to be directed toward Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Dust storms from Iraq and Saudi Arabia transported by northwesterly winds, locally called shamal wind, cause reduced visibility in the months of June and July.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The seas around Bahrain are very shallow, heating up quickly in the summer to produce very high humidity, especially at night.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] This is in stark contrast to other desert climates such as those of Baghdad or Phoenix.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Summer temperatures may reach up to 40 °C (104 °F) under the right conditions.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Rainfall in Bahrain is minimal and irregular.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Precipitation mostly occurs in winter, with an average of 70.8 millimetres or 2.8 inches of rainfall recorded annually.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The country experienced widespread flooding in April 2024 after heavy rainfall affected the Gulf region.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Due to climate change Bahrain is experiencing more frequent extreme heat, drought, flooding and dust storms and the threat of sea level rise.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] These conditions threaten Bahrain's food and water security, and are expected to become more severe in the future.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Despite being a relatively low-emitting country overall, Bahrain was the second highest greenhouse gas emitter per capita in 2023, at approximately 42 tonnes per person.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Most of Bahrain's emissions arise from burning fossil fuels in the energy sector.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The nation has committed to net zero by 2060 and also aims to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 30% by 2035.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] More than 330 species of birds were recorded in the Bahrain archipelago, 26 species of which breed in the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Millions of migratory birds pass through the Persian Gulf region in the winter and autumn months.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] One globally endangered species, *Chlamydotis undulata*, is a regular migrant in the autumn.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The many islands and shallow seas of Bahrain are globally important for the breeding of the Socotra cormorant; up to 100,000 pairs of these birds were recorded over the Hawar Islands.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain's national bird is the bulbul while its national animal is the Arabian oryx.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] And the national flower of Bahrain is the beloved Deena.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Only 18 species of mammals are found in Bahrain, animals such as gazelles, desert rabbits and hedgehogs are common in the wild but the Arabian oryx was hunted to extinction on the island.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Twenty-five species of amphibians and reptiles were recorded as well as 21 species of butterflies and 307 species of flora.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The marine biotopes are diverse and include extensive sea grass beds and mudflats, patchy coral reefs as well as offshore islands.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Sea grass beds are important foraging grounds for some threatened species such as dugongs and the green turtle.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] In 2003, Bahrain banned the capture of sea cows, marine turtles and dolphins within its territorial waters.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The Hawar Islands Protected Area provides valuable feeding and breeding grounds for a variety of migratory seabirds; it is an internationally recognised site for bird migration.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] The breeding colony of Socotra cormorant on Hawar Islands is the largest in the world, and the dugongs foraging around the archipelago form the second-largest dugong aggregation after Australia.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p01] Bahrain has five designated protected areas, four of which are marine environments.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain is a semi-constitutional monarchy headed by King Shaikh Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] King Hamad enjoys wide executive powers which include appointing the prime minister and his ministers, commanding the Bahrain Defence Force, chairing the Higher Judicial Council, appointing the parliament's upper house and dissolving its elected lower house.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The head of government is the prime minister.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2010, about half of the cabinet was composed of the Al Khalifa family.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain has a bicameral National Assembly (*al-Majlis al-Watani*) consisting of the Shura Council (*Majlis Al-Shura*) with 40 seats and the Council of Representatives (*Majlis Al-Nuwab*) with 40 seats.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The forty members of the Shura are appointed by the king.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In the Council of Representatives, 40 members are elected by absolute majority vote in gerrymandered single-member constituencies to serve four-year terms.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The appointed council "exercises a *de facto* veto" over the "rubber-stamp" elected, because draft acts must be approved so they may pass into law.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] After approval, the king may ratify and issue the act or return it within six months to the National Assembly where it may only pass into law if approved by two-thirds of both councils.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 1973, the country held its first parliamentary elections; however, two years later, the late emir dissolved the parliament and suspended the constitution after parliament rejected the State Security Law.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The period between 2002 and 2010 saw three parliamentary elections.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The first, held in 2002 was boycotted by the opposition, Al Wefaq, which won a majority in the second in 2006 and third in 2010.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] A 2011 by-election was held to replace 18 members of Al Wefaq who resigned in protest against government crackdown.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] According to the V-Dem Democracy indices Bahrain is 2023 the 4th least electoral democratic country in the Middle East.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Similarly, according to International IDEA's Global State of Democracy (GSoD) Indices and Democracy Tracker, Bahrain performs in the low range on overall democratic measures, with particular weaknesses in social group equality, judicial independence, and freedom of association and assembly.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The opening up of politics saw big gains for both Shīa and Sunnī fundamentalists in elections, which gave them a parliamentary platform to pursue their policies.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] It gave a new prominence to clerics within the political system, with the most senior Shia religious leader, Sheikh Isa Qassim, playing a vital role.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] This was especially evident when in 2005 the government called off the Shia branch of the "Family law" after over 100,000 Shia took to the streets.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Muslim fundamentalists opposed the law because "neither elected MPs nor the government has the authority to change the law because these institutions could misinterpret the word of God".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The law was supported by women activists who said they were "suffering in silence".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] They managed to organise a rally attended by 500 participants.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Ghada Jamsheer, a leading woman activist said the government was using the law as a "bargaining tool with opposition Islamic groups".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Analysts of democratisation in the Middle East cite the fundamentalist' references to respect human rights in their justification for these programmes as evidence that these groups can serve as a progressive force in the region.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Some fundamentalist parties have been particularly critical of the government's readiness to sign international treaties such as the United Nations' International Convention on Civil and Political Rights.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] This why we have eyes from the American Embassy watching us during our sessions, to ensure things are swinging their way".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The kingdom has a small but professional and well-equipped military called the Bahrain Defence Force (BDF), numbering around 8,200 personnel, including 6,000 in the Royal Bahraini Army, 700 in the Royal Bahraini Naval Force, and 1,500 in the Royal Bahraini Air Force.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The BDF command structure includes the Bahrain Royal Guard, which is the size of one battalion and has its own armored vehicles and artillery.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Bahrain National Guard is separate from the BDF, though it is tasked with assisting it in defense from external threats, and it has about 2,000 personnel.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The supreme commander of the Bahraini military is King Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The deputy supreme commander is the Crown Prince, Salman bin Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Commander-in-Chief of the BDF has been Field Marshal Khalifa bin Ahmed Al Khalifa since 2008.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The BDF is primarily equipped with American made equipment, such as the F-16 Fighting Falcon, F-5 Freedom Fighter, UH-60 Blackhawk, M60A3 tanks, and the ex-USS *Jack Williams*, an Oliver Hazard Perry class frigate renamed the RBNS *Sabha*.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In August 2020, the UK's *HMS Clyde* was transferred to the Royal Bahrain Naval Force, with the ship renamed as RBNS *Al-Zubara*.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In January 2024 the Bahraini Navy received a second *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class frigate, the former USS *Robert G.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bradley*, which was renamed RBNS *Khalid bin Ali*.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain was the first country in the Gulf to operate the F-16.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2024 the Royal Bahraini Air Force expects to receive 16 aircraft of the modernised F-16 Block 70 variant, in addition to its current 20 F-16C/D and 12 F-5E/F fighters.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Royal Bahraini Army has 180 M60A3 main battle tanks, with 100 in active service and 80 in storage.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Government of Bahrain has close relations with America, having signed a cooperative agreement with the American military, and has provided America a base in Juffair since the early 1990s.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] An American naval presence has existed since 1948.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] This is the home of the headquarters for Commander, *American Naval Forces Central Command* (COMUSNAVCENT) / *American Fifth Fleet* (COMFIFTHFLT), and around 6,000 American military personnel.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain participates in the Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen against the Houthis and forces loyal to former President Ali Abdullah Saleh, who was deposed in the 2011 Arab Spring uprising.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The permanent British Royal Navy base at Mina Salman, *HMS Jufair*, was officially opened in April 2018.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain has established bilateral relations with 190 countries worldwide.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] As of 2012, Bahrain maintains a network of 25 embassies, three consulates and four permanent missions to the Arab League, United Nations and European Union respectively.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] America designated Bahrain a major non-NATO ally in 2001.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain plays a modest, moderating role in regional politics and adheres to the views of the Arab League on Middle East peace and Palestinian rights by supporting the two state solution.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain is also one of the founding members of the Gulf Cooperation Council.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Relations with Iran tend to be tense as a result of a failed coup in 1981 which Bahrain blames Iran for and occasional claims of Iranian sovereignty over Bahrain by ultra-conservative elements in the Iranian public.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2016, following the storming of the Saudi embassy in Tehran, both Saudi Arabia and Bahrain cut diplomatic relations with Iran.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain and Israel established bilateral relations in 2020 under the Bahrain–Israel normalisation agreement.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain is the 81st most peaceful country in the world, according to the 2024 Global Peace Index.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The period between 1975 and 1999, known as the "State Security Law Era", saw wide range of human rights violations including arbitrary arrests, detention without trial, torture and forced exile.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] After Emir (now King) Hamad Al Khalifa succeeded his father Isa Al Khalifa in 1999, he introduced wide reforms and human rights improved significantly.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] These moves were described by Amnesty International as representing a "historic period of human rights".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Consensual male and female homosexual relations between adults over the age of 21 are legal in Bahrain, which is the only Muslim Gulf country where it has been legal since 1976.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Human rights conditions started to decline by 2007 when torture began to be employed again.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2011, Human Rights Watch described the country's human rights situation as "dismal".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Due to this, Bahrain lost some of the high International rankings it had gained before.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2011, Bahrain was criticised for its crackdown on the Arab spring uprising.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In September, a government-appointed commission confirmed reports of grave human rights violations, including systematic torture.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The government promised to introduce reforms and avoid repeating the "painful events".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] However, reports by human rights organisations Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch issued in April 2012 said the same violations were still happening.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Amnesty International's 2015 report on the country points to the continued suppression of dissent, restricted freedom of expression, unjust imprisonment, and frequent torture and other ill-treatment of its citizens.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] As of October 2014, Bahrain is ruled by an "authoritarian regime" and is rated as "Not Free" by America-based non-governmental Freedom House.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Freedom House continues to label Bahrain as "not free" in its 2021 report.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] On 7 July 2016, the European Parliament adopted, with a large majority, a resolution condemning human rights abuses performed by Bahraini authorities, and strongly called for an end to the ongoing repression against the country's human rights defenders, political opposition and civil society.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In its latest report Amnesty International accused both the American and British governments of turning a blind eye to horrific abuses of human rights by the ruling Bahraini regime.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] On 31 January 2018, Amnesty International reported that the Bahraini government expelled four of its citizens after having revoked their nationality in 2012, turning them into stateless people.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] On 21 February 2018, human rights activist Nabeel Rajab was sentenced to a further five years in jail for tweets and documentation of human rights violations.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] On behalf of the ruling family, Bahraini police have received training on how to deal with public protests from the British government.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] On 11 July 2020, a government watchdog in Bahrain claimed that the confessions of two pro-democracy campaigners were extracted by torture.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Mohammed Ramadhan and Husain Moosa from Bahrain were leading figures in the pro-democracy protests of 2011.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] They were arrested in 2014 and accused of killing a police officer.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] On 13 July 2020, the highest Court in Bahrain overruled the previous judgment and upheld the death sentences for both men.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The 761-page *World Report 2021* published by the *Human Rights Watch* in January 2021 revealed that the situation of human rights did not improve in Bahrain in 2020.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] It highlighted that the repression against social media activities escalated, death sentences were upheld by the courts against opposition activists after unfair trials, and the critics continued to be prosecuted for peaceful expression.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The country also increased the use of the death penalty, while it denied medical treatment to some of the prominent opposition figures being kept in detention.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Human Rights Watch said that Bahrain uses several repressive tools to silence and punish every person who dares to criticise the government.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In March 2021, Human Rights Watch (HRW) and the London-based Bahrain Institute for Rights and Democracy claimed that 13 children aged between 11 and 17 were beaten and threatened with rape and electric shocks after being detained in protest-related cases.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Women in Bahrain acquired voting rights and the right to stand in national elections in the 2002 election.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] However, no women were elected to office in that year's polls.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In response to the failure of women candidates, six were appointed to the Shura Council, which also includes representatives of the kingdom's indigenous Jewish and Christian communities.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Nada Haffadh became the country's first female cabinet minister on her appointment as Minister of Health in 2004.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The quasi-governmental women's group, the Supreme Council for Women, trained female candidates to take part in the 2006 general election.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] When Bahrain was elected to head the United Nations General Assembly in 2006 it appointed lawyer and women's rights activist Haya bint Rashid Al Khalifa President of the United Nations General Assembly, only the third woman in history to head the world body.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Female activist Ghada Jamsheer said "The government used women's rights as a decorative tool on the international level." She referred to the reforms as "artificial and marginal" and accused the government of "hinder[ing] non-governmental women societies".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2006, Lateefa Al Gaood became the first female MP after winning by default.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The number rose to four after the 2011 by-elections.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2008, Houda Nonoo was appointed ambassador to the United States making her the first Jewish ambassador of any Arab country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2011, Alice Samaan, a Christian woman, was appointed ambassador to Britain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The predominant forms of media in Bahrain consists of weekly and daily newspapers, television, and radio.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Newspapers are widely available in multiple languages such as Arabic, English, Malayalam, etc. to support the varied population.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] *Akhbar Al Khaleej* (أخبار الخليج) and *Al Ayam* (الأيام) are examples of major Arabic newspapers published daily.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] *Gulf Daily News* and *Daily Tribune* publish daily newspapers in English.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] *Gulf Madhyamam* is a newspaper published in Malayalam.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The country's television network operates five networks, all of which are by the Information Affairs Authority.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Radio, much like the television network, is mostly state-run and usually in Arabic.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] *Radio Bahrain* is a long-running English language radio station, and *Radio Mirchi 104.2* is a radio station serving the large expatriate population from the Indian subcontinent living in the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] By June 2012, Bahrain had 961,000 internet users.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The platform "provides a welcome free space for journalists, although one that is increasingly monitored", according to Reporters Without Borders.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Rigorous filtering targets political, human rights, religious material and content deemed obscene.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bloggers and other netizens were among those detained during protests in 2011.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahraini journalists risk prosecution for offences that include "undermining" the government and religion.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Journalists were targeted by officials during anti-government protests in 2011.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Three editors from the now-banned opposition daily *Al-Wasat* were sacked and later fined for publishing "false" news.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Several foreign correspondents were expelled.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] An independent commission, set up to look into the unrest, found that state media coverage was at times inflammatory.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] It said opposition groups suffered from lack of access to mainstream media and recommended that the government "consider relaxing censorship".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Assessments by Reporters Without Borders have consistently found Bahrain to be one of the most world's most restrictive regimes.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] According to a January 2006 report by the United Nations Economic and Social Commission for Western Asia, Bahrain has the fastest-growing economy in the Arab world.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain's economy is ranked the 55th freest in the 2025 *Index of Economic Freedom* and 4th out of 14 countries in the Middle East/North Africa region.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2008, Bahrain was named the world's fastest-growing financial centre by the City of London's Global Financial Centres Index.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain's banking and financial services sector, particularly Muslim banking, have benefited from the regional boom driven by demand for oil.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Petroleum production and processing is Bahrain's most exported product, accounting for 60% of export receipts, 70% of government revenues, and 11% of GDP.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Aluminium production is the second-most exported product, followed by finance and construction materials.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Economic conditions have fluctuated with the changing price of oil since 1985, for example during and following the Persian Gulf crisis of 1990–91.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] With its highly developed communication and transport facilities, Bahrain is home to a number of multinational firms and construction proceeds on several major industrial projects.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] A large share of exports consists of petroleum products made from imported crude oil, which accounted for 51% of the country's imports in 2007.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In October 2008, the Bahraini government introduced a long-term economic vision for Bahrain known as 'Vision 2030' which aims to transform Bahrain into a diversified and sustainable economy.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Avenues is one such example of the recent developments.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] It is a waterfront facing shopping mall that was opened in October 2019.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain depends heavily on food imports to feed its growing population—it imports large amounts of meat and 75% of its fruit.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Since only 2.9% of the country's land is arable, agriculture contributes to 0.5% of Bahrain's GDP.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2004, Bahrain signed the Bahrain–US Free Trade Agreement, which will reduce certain trade barriers between the two nations.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2011, due to the combination of the Great Recession and the 2011 Bahraini uprising, its GDP growth rate decreased to 1.3%, which was the lowest growth rate since 1994.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The country's public debt in 2020 is $44.5 billion, or 130% of GDP.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] It is expected to rise to 155 per cent of GDP in 2026, according to IMF estimates.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The military expenditure is the main reason for this increase in debt.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Access to biocapacity in Bahrain is much lower than the world average.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2016, Bahrain had 0.52 global hectares of biocapacity per person within its territory, much less than the world average of 1.6 global hectares per person.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2016, Bahrain used 8.6 global hectares of biocapacity per person – their ecological footprint of consumption.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] This means they use 16.5 times as much biocapacity as Bahrain contains.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] As a result, Bahrain is running a biocapacity deficit.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Unemployment, especially among the young, and the depletion of both oil and underground water resources are major long-term economic problems.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2008, the jobless figure was at 4%, with women overrepresented at 85% of the total.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2007 Bahrain became the first Arab country to institute unemployment benefits as part of a series of labour reforms instigated under Minister of Labour, Majeed Al Alawi.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] As of Q2 2023, total employment in Bahrain stood at 770,129 workers.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] This included both Bahraini and Non-Bahraini workers.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] These employment levels represented a full recovery of employment since the downturn caused by the COVID pandemic.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain have energy and electricity production, consumption and imports which is making a net energy exporter.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain was the first place on the Arabian side of the Persian Gulf where oil was discovered.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The First Oil Well, Bahrain situated below Jabal al Dukhan has operated since 1932.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] It was operated by Bahrain Petroleum Company.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2023, the petroleum production of Bahrain was rated at about 189,000 barrels per day.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The petroleum reserves were quoted as 168 million barrels in 2023.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] As of 2023, Bahrain was said to produce 16.7 billion cubic metres (bcm) of natural gas per year and have reserves of 68 bcm.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] As a tourist destination, Bahrain received over eleven million visitors in 2019.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Most of these are from the surrounding Arab states, although an increasing number hail from outside the region due to growing awareness of the kingdom's heritage and partly due to its higher profile as a result of the Bahrain Grand Prix.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The kingdom combines modern Arab culture and the archaeological legacy of five thousand years of civilisation.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The island is home to forts including Qalat Al Bahrain which has been listed by UNESCO as a World Heritage Site.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Bahrain National Museum has artefacts from the country's history dating back to the island's first human inhabitants some 9000 years ago and the Beit Al Quran (Arabic: بيت القرآن, meaning: the House of Qur'an) is a museum that holds Muslim artefacts of the Qur'an.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Tree of Life, a 400-year-old tree that grows in the Sakhir desert with no nearby water, is also a popular tourist attraction.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bird watching (primarily in the Hawar Islands), scuba diving, and horse riding are popular tourist activities in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Many tourists from nearby Saudi Arabia and across the region visit Manama primarily for the shopping malls in the capital Manama, such as the Bahrain City Centre and Seef Mall in the Seef district of Manama.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Manama Souq and *Gold Souq* in the old district of Manama are also popular with tourists.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In January 2019 the state-run Bahrain News Agency announced the summer 2019 opening of an underwater theme park covering about 100,000 square metres with a sunken Boeing 747 as the site's centrepiece.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The project is a partnership between the Supreme Council for Environment, Bahrain Tourism and Exhibitions Authority (BTEA), and private investors.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain hopes scuba divers from around the world will visit the underwater park, which will also include artificial coral reefs, a copy of a Bahraini pearl merchant's house, and sculptures.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The park is intended to become the world's largest eco-friendly underwater theme park.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Since 2005, Bahrain hosts an annual festival in March, titled *Spring of Culture*, which features internationally renowned musicians and artists performing in concerts.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Manama was named the Arab Capital of Culture for 2012 and *Capital of Arab Tourism* for 2013 by the Arab League and Asian Tourism for 2014 with the Gulf Capital of Tourism for 2016 by The Gulf Cooperation Council.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The 2012 festival featured concerts starring Andrea Bocelli, Julio Iglesias and other musicians.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Kingdom of Bahrain introduced the Value Added Tax with effect from 1 January 2019.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] This is a multipoint tax on the sale of goods and services in Kingdom of Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] This has been managed by the government through the national bureau of revenue.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The ultimate burden of this tax is passed on the consumer.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] To start with the maximum rate of VAT was 5% which is increased to 10% with effect from 1 January 2022.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The government of Bahrain is assuring compliance through high penalties on defaults and tighter audits.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] This first of its kind VAT has invited qualified chartered accounting firms mainly from India to advise on VAT matters.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Firms like KPMG, KeyPoint, Assure Consulting and APMH have set up offices looking at the need for consulting in this domain of VAT.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain has one main international airport, the Bahrain International Airport (BAH) which is located on the island of Muharraq, in the north-east.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The airport handled almost 100,000 flights and more than 9.5 million passengers in 2019.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] On 28 January 2021, Bahrain opened its new airport terminal as part of its economic vision 2030.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The new airport terminal is capable of handling 14 million passengers and is a big boost to the country's aviation sector.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain's national carrier, Gulf Air operates and bases itself in the BIA.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain has a well-developed road network, particularly in Manama.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The discovery of oil in the early 1930s accelerated the creation of multiple roads and highways in Bahrain, connecting several isolated villages, such as Budaiya, to Manama.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] To the east, a bridge connected Manama to Muharraq since 1929, a new causeway was built in 1941 which replaced the old wooden bridge.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Currently there are three modern bridges connecting the two locations.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Transits between the two islands peaked after the construction of the Bahrain International Airport in 1932.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Ring roads and highways were later built to connect Manama to the villages of the Northern Governorate and towards towns in central and southern Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The four main islands and all the towns and villages are linked by well-constructed roads.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] A causeway stretching over 2.8 km (2 mi), connect Manama with Muharraq Island, and another bridge joins Sitra to the main island.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The King Fahd Causeway, measuring 24 km (15 mi), links Bahrain with the Saudi Arabian mainland via the island of Umm an-Nasan.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] It was completed in December 1986, and financed by Saudi Arabia.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2008, there were 17,743,495 passengers transiting through the causeway.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] A second causeway, which will have both road and rail connection, between Bahrain and Saudi Arabia called 'King Hamad Causeway' is currently being discussed and is in the planning phase.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain's port of Mina Salman is the main seaport of the country and consists of 15 berths.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2001, Bahrain had a merchant fleet of eight ships of 1,000 GT or over, totalling 270,784 GT.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Private vehicles and taxis are the primary means of transportation in the city.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] A nationwide metro system is currently under construction and is due to be operational by 2025.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The telecommunications sector in Bahrain officially started in 1981 with the establishment of Bahrain's first telecommunications company, Batelco and until 2004, it monopolised the sector.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 1981, there were more than 45,000 telephones in use in the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] By 1999, Batelco had more than 100,000 mobile contracts.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2002, under pressure from international bodies, Bahrain implemented its telecommunications law which included the establishment of an independent *Telecommunications Regulatory Authority* (TRA).
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2004, Zain (a rebranded version of MTC Vodafone) started operations in Bahrain and in 2010 VIVA (owned by STC Group) became the third company to provide mobile services.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain has been connected to the internet since 1995 with the country's domain suffix being '.bh'.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The country's connectivity score (a statistic which measures both Internet access and fixed and mobile telephone lines) is 210.4 per cent per person, while the regional average in Arab States of the Persian Gulf is 135.37 per cent.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The number of Bahraini internet users has risen from 40,000 in 2000 to 250,000 in 2008, or from 5.95 to 33 per cent of the population.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] As of August 2013, the TRA has licensed 22 Internet service providers.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The *Bahraini Economic Vision 2030* published in 2008 does not indicate how the stated goal of shifting from an economy built on oil wealth to a productive, globally competitive economy will be attained.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain has already diversified its exports to some extent, out of necessity.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] It has the smallest hydrocarbon reserves of any Persian Gulf state, producing 48,000 barrels per day from its one onshore field.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The bulk of the country's revenue comes from its share in the offshore field administered by Saudi Arabia.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The gas reserve in Bahrain is expected to last for less than 27 years, leaving the country with few sources of capital to pursue the development of new industries.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Investment in research and development remained very low in 2013.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Apart from the Ministry of Education and the Higher Education Council, the two main hives of activity in science, technology, and innovation are the University of Bahrain (established in 1986) and the Bahrain Centre for Strategic, International, and Energy Studies.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The latter was founded in 2009 to undertake research with a focus on strategic security and energy issues to encourage new thinking and influence policymaking.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain hopes to build a science culture within the kingdom and to encourage technological innovation, among other goals.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2013, the Bahrain Science Centre was launched as an interactive educational facility targeting 6- to 18-year-olds.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The topics covered by current exhibitions include junior engineering, human health, the five senses, Earth sciences and biodiversity.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In April 2014, Bahrain launched its National Space Science Agency.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The agency has been working to ratify international space-related agreements such as the Outer Space Treaty, the Rescue Agreement, the Space Liability Convention, the Registration Convention and the Moon Agreement.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The agency plans to establish infrastructure for the observation of both outer space and the Earth.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In November 2008, an agreement was signed to establish a Regional Centre for Information and Communication Technology in Manama under the auspices of UNESCO.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The aim is to establish a knowledge hub for the six-member states of the Gulf Cooperation Council.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In March 2012, the centre hosted two high-level workshops on ICTs and education.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2013, Bahrain topped the Arab world for internet penetration (90% of the population), trailed by the United Arab Emirates (86%) and Qatar (85%).
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Just half of Bahrainis and Qataris (53%) and two-thirds of those in the United Arab Emirates (64%) had access in 2009.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2012, the government devoted 2.6% of GDP to education, one of the lowest ratios in the Arab world.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] This ratio was on a par with investment in education in Lebanon and higher only than that in Qatar (2.4% in 2008) and Sudan (2.2% in 2009).
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain was ranked 72nd in the Global Innovation Index in 2024, but jumped to the 62nd rank according to GII 2025.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain invests little in research and development.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2009 and 2013, this investment reportedly amounted to 0.04% of GDP, although the data were incomplete, covering only the higher education sector.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The lack of comprehensive data on research and development poses a challenge for policymakers, as data inform evidence-based policymaking.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The available data for researchers in 2013 cover only the higher education sector.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Here, the number of researchers is equivalent to 50 per million inhabitants, compared to a global average for all employment sectors of 1,083 per million.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The University of Bahrain had over 20,000 students in 2014, 65% of whom are women, and around 900 faculty members, 40% of whom are women.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] From 1986 to 2014, university staff published 5,500 papers and books.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The university spent about US$11 million per year on research in 2014, which was conducted by a contingent of 172 men and 128 women.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Women thus made up 43% of researchers at the University of Bahrain in 2014.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain was one of 11 Arab states which counted a majority of female university graduates in science and engineering in 2014.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Women accounted for 66% of graduates in natural sciences, 28% of those in engineering and 77% of those in health and welfare.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] It is harder to judge the contribution of women to research, as the data for 2013 only cover the higher education sector.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2014, Bahraini scientists published 155 articles in internationally catalogued journals, according to Thomson Reuters' Web of Science (Science Citation Index Expanded).
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] This corresponds to 15 articles per million inhabitants, compared to a global average of 176 per million inhabitants in 2013.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Scientific output has risen slowly from 93 articles in 2005 and remains modest.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] By 2014, only Mauritania and Palestine had a smaller output in this database among Arab states.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Between 2008 and 2014, Bahraini scientists collaborated most with their peers from Saudi Arabia (137 articles), followed by Egypt (101), the Britain (93), the America (89) and Tunisia (75).
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2010, Bahrain's population was 1.2 million, of which 568,399 were Bahraini and 666,172 were non-nationals.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] It had risen from 1.05 million (517,368 non-nationals) in 2007, the year when Bahrain's population crossed the one million mark.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Though a majority of the population is Middle Eastern, a sizeable number of people from South Asia live in the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2008, approximately 290,000 Indian nationals lived in Bahrain, making them the single largest expatriate community in the country, the majority from the south Indian state of Kerala.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain is the fourth most densely populated sovereign state in the world with a population density of 1,646 people per km2 in 2010.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The only sovereign states with larger population densities are city states.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Much of this population is concentrated in the north of the country with the Southern Governorate being the least densely populated part.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The north of the country is so urbanised that it is considered by some to be one large metropolitan area.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Shia Bahrainis are divided into two main ethnic groups: Baharna and Ajam.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Baharna are ethnically Arab, and the Ajam are of Persian origin.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Shia Persians form large communities in Manama and Muharraq.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] A small minority of Shia Bahrainis are ethnic Hasawis from Al-Hasa.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Sunni Bahrainis are mainly divided into two main ethnic groups: Arabs (al Arab) and Huwala.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Sunni Arabs are the most influential ethnic group in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] They hold most government positions and the Bahraini monarchy are Sunni Arabs.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Sunni Arabs have traditionally lived in areas such as Zallaq, Muharraq, West Riffa and Hawar islands.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Huwala are descendants of Sunni Iranians; some of them are Sunni Persians, while others Sunni Arabs.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Most African Bahrainis come from East Africa and have traditionally lived in Muharraq Island and Riffa.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The state religion of Bahrain is Islam and most Bahrainis are Muslim.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The majority of Bahraini Muslims are Sunni Muslims with a recent estimate giving them a 51% majority and Shia Muslims with a 49% minority.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] It was previously one of the three countries in the Middle East in which Shia were the majority, the other two nations being Iraq and Iran, though the rise of Sunni migrants made Sunnis the majority.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Unofficial sources estimate sectarian identification to be approximately 55% Sunni and 45% Shia.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Public surveys are rare in Bahrain, but the US department of state's report on religious freedom in Bahrain estimated that Shias constituted approximately 55% of Bahrain's citizen population in 2018.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The royal family and most Bahrani elites are Sunni.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The country's two Muslim communities are united on some issues, but disagree sharply on others.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Shia have often complained of being politically and economically discriminated against in Bahrain; as a result, most of the protestors in the Bahraini uprising of 2011 were Shia.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Christians in Bahrain make up about 14.5% of the population.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] There is a native Christian community in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Non-Muslim Bahraini residents numbered 367,683 per the 2010 census, most of whom are Christians.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Expatriate Christians make up the majority of Christians in Bahrain, while native Christian Bahrainis (who hold Bahraini citizenship) make up a smaller community.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Native Christians who hold Bahraini citizenship number approximately 1,000 persons.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Alees Samaan, a former Bahraini ambassador to Britain is a native Christian.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain also has a native Jewish community numbering thirty-seven Bahraini citizens.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Various sources cite Bahrain's native Jewish community as being from 36 to 50 people.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] According to Bahraini writer Nancy Khedouri, the Jewish community of Bahrain is one of the youngest in the world, having its origins in the migration of a few families to the island from then-Iraq and then-Iran in the late 1880s.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Houda Nonoo, former ambassador to America, is Jewish.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] There is also a Hindu community on the island.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] They constitute the third largest religious group.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Shrinathji temple located in old Manama is the oldest Hindu temple in the GCC and the Arab world.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] It is over 200 years old and was built by the Thattai Hindu community in 1817.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] According to the 2001 census, 81.2% of Bahrain's population was Muslim, 10% were Christian, and 9.8% practised Hinduism or other religions.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The 2010 census records that the Muslim proportion had fallen to 70.2% (the 2010 census did not differentiate between the non-Muslim religions).
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Arabic is the official language of Bahrain, though English is widely used.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrani Arabic is the most widely spoken dialect of the Arabic language and is different from standard Arabic, like all Arabic dialects.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Arabic plays an important role in political life, as, according to Bahrain's constitution, an MP must be fluent in Arabic to stand for parliament.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Balochi is the second largest and widely spoken language in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Baloch are fluent in Arabic and Balochi.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Among the Bahraini and non-Bahraini population, many people speak Persian, the official language of Iran, or Urdu, an official language in Pakistan and a regional language in India.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Nepali is also widely spoken in the Nepalese workers and Gurkha Soldiers community.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Malayalam, Tamil, Telugu, Bangla and Hindi are spoken among significant Indian communities.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] All commercial institutions and road signs are bilingual, displaying both English and Arabic.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain boasts a diverse education system that includes a variety of private schools offering international curricula.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Among these are British, American, and other international schools, catering to a wide range of educational needs.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Education is compulsory for children between the ages of 6 and 14.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Education is free for Bahraini citizens in government schools, with the Bahraini Ministry of Education providing free textbooks.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Coeducation is not used in government schools, with boys and girls segregated into separate schools.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Qur'anic schools (*Kuttab*) were the only form of education in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] They were traditional schools aimed at teaching children and youth the reading of the Qur'an.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] After World War I, Bahrain became open to western influences, and a demand for modern educational institutions appeared.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] 1919 marked the beginning of modern government school system in Bahrain when the Al-Hidaya Al-Khalifia School for boys opened in Muharraq.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 1926, the Education Committee opened the second government school for boys in Manama, and in 1928 the first government school for girls was opened in Muharraq.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2011, there were 126,981 students studying in government schools.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2004, King Hamad ibn Isa Al Khalifa introduced the "King Hamad Schools of Future" project that uses Information Communication Technology to support K–12 education in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The project's objective is to connect all schools within the kingdom with the Internet.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In addition to British intermediate schools, the island is served by the Bahrain School (BS).
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The BS is an American Department of Defense school that provides a K–12 curriculum including International Baccalaureate offerings.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] There are also international schools that offer either the IB Diploma Programme or Britain's A-Levels.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain also encourages institutions of higher learning, drawing on expatriate talent and the increasing pool of Bahrain nationals returning from abroad with advanced degrees.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The University of Bahrain was established for standard undergraduate and graduate study, and the King Abdulaziz University College of Health Sciences, operating under the direction of the Ministry of Health, trains physicians, nurses, pharmacists and paramedics.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The 2001 National Action Charter paved the way for the formation of international universities such as the Ahlia University in Manama and University College of Bahrain in Saar.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Royal University for Women (RUW), established in 2005, was the first purpose-built, international university in Bahrain dedicated solely to educating women.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The University of London External has appointed MCG (Management Consultancy Group) as the regional representative office in Bahrain for distance learning programmes.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] MCG is one of the oldest international institutes in the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Institutes have also opened which educate South Asian students, such as the Pakistan Urdu School, Bahrain and the Indian School, Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] A few prominent institutions are the American University of Bahrain established in 2019, the Bahrain Institute of Banking and Finance, the Ernst & Young Training Institute, and the Birla Institute of Technology International Centre.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2004, the Royal College of Surgeons in Ireland (RCSI) set up a constituent medical university in the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In addition to the Arabian Gulf University, AMA International University and the College of Health Sciences, these are the only medical schools in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain has a universal health care system, dating back to 1960.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Government-provided health care is free to Bahraini citizens and heavily subsidised for non-Bahrainis.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Healthcare expenditure accounted for 4.5% of Bahrain's GDP, according to the World Health Organisation.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahraini physicians and nurses form a majority of the country's workforce in the health sector, unlike neighbouring Gulf states.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The first hospital in Bahrain was the American Mission Hospital, which opened in 1893 as a dispensary.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The first public hospital, and also tertiary hospital, to open in Bahrain was the Salmaniya Medical Complex, in the Salmaniya district of Manama, in 1957.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Private hospitals are also present throughout the country, such as the International Hospital of Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The life expectancy in Bahrain is 73 for males and 76 for females.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Compared to many countries in the region, the prevalence of AIDS and HIV is relatively low.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Malaria and tuberculosis (TB) do not constitute major problems in Bahrain as neither disease is indigenous to the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] As a result, cases of malaria and TB have declined in recent decades with cases of contractions amongst Bahraini nationals becoming rare.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] The Ministry of Health sponsors regular vaccination campaigns against TB and other diseases such as hepatitis B.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Bahrain has an obesity epidemic, with 28.9% of all males and 38.2% of all females are classified as obese in 2012.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2010, Bahrain had one of the highest prevalence of diabetes in the world, at 5th place.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] In 2010, more than 15% of the Bahraini population were affected by diabetes, and they account for 5% of deaths in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Cardiovascular diseases account for 32% of all deaths in Bahrain, being the number one cause of death in the country (the second being cancer).
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] Sickle-cell anaemia and thalassaemia are prevalent in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p02] 18% of Bahrainis are carriers of sickle-cell anaemia.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Islam is the main religion, and Bahrainis are known for their tolerance towards the practice of other faiths.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Intermarriages between Bahrainis and expatriates are not uncommon—there are many Filipino Bahrainis like Filipino child actress Mona Marbella Al-Alawi.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Rules regarding female attire are generally relaxed compared to regional neighbours; the traditional attire of women usually include the hijab or the abaya.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Although the traditional male attire is the thobe, which also includes traditional headdresses such as the keffiyeh, ghutra and agal, Western clothing is common in the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Although Bahrain legalised homosexuality in 1976, many homosexuals have since been arrested, often for violating broadly written laws against public immorality and public indecency.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The modern art movement in the country officially emerged in the 1950s, culminating in the establishment of an art society.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Expressionism and surrealism, as well as calligraphic art are the popular forms of art in the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Abstract expressionism has gained popularity in recent decades.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Pottery-making and textile-weaving are also popular products that were widely made in Bahraini villages.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Arabic calligraphy grew in popularity as the Bahraini government was an active patron in Muslim art, culminating in the establishment of a Muslim museum, Beit Al Quran.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The Bahrain National Museum houses a permanent contemporary art exhibition.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The annual Spring of Culture festival run by the Bahrain Authority for Culture and Antiquities has become a popular event promoting performance arts in the kingdom.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The architecture of Bahrain is similar to that of its neighbours in the Persian Gulf.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The wind tower, which generates natural ventilation in a house, is a common sight on old buildings, particularly in the old districts of Manama and Muharraq.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Literature retains a strong tradition in the country; most traditional writers and poets write in the classical Arabic style.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] In recent years, the number of younger poets influenced by western literature are rising, most writing in free verse and often including political or personal content.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Ali Al Shargawi, a decorated longtime poet, was described in 2011 by *Al Shorfa* as the literary icon of Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] In literature, Bahrain was the site of the ancient land of Dilmun mentioned in the Epic of Gilgamesh.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Legend also states that it was the location of the Garden of Eden.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The music style in Bahrain is similar to that of its neighbours.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The Khaliji style of music, which is folk music, is popular in the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The sawt style of music, which involves a complex form of urban music, performed by an Oud (plucked lute), a violin and mirwas (a drum), is also popular in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Ali Bahar was one of the most famous singers in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] He performed his music with his Band *Al-Ekhwa* (*The Brothers*).
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain was also the site of the first recording studio amongst the Persian Gulf states.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] As for cultural sites, residents, visitors, and tourists can re-live history through Bahrain's many historical sites.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain is the second nation after the United States to host International Mixed Martial Arts (MMA) Federation World Championships of Amateur MMA in partnership with Brave Combat Federation.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain recorded an influx in global athletes visiting the nation for MMA training during 2017.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Brave Combat Federation is a Bahrain-based MMA promotion that has hosted events in 30 nations which is a record for hosting events in most number of nations by an MMA promotion.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain MMA Federation (BMMAF) has been set up under the patronage of Sheikh Khalid bin Hamad Al Khalifa and the jurisdiction of the Sports Minister, Sheikh Nasser bin Hamad Al Khalifa.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The development of MMA in the nation is convened through KHK MMA, which owns Brave Combat Federation which is the largest Mixed Martial Arts promotion in the Middle East.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain will be hosting Amateur World Championships 2017 in association with International Mixed Martial Arts Federation.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain will be the first Asian and Arab country to host the amateur MMA championship.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain is also home to KHK MMA Fight Team, that facilitates training for some of the prominent talent in Mixed Martial Arts in the world who compete in BRAVE Combat Federation, PFL, and UFC.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] In 2018, Cricket was introduced in Bahrain under the initiative of KHK Sports and Exelon.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain Premier League 2018 comprised six franchise squads of 13 resident cricketers competing in the T20 format.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The teams were SRam MRam Falcons, Kalaam Knight-Riders, Intex Lions, Bahrain Super Giants, Four Square Challengers and Awan Warriors.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Football is also a popular sport in Bahrain.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain's national football team has competed multiple times at the Asian Cup, Arab Nations Cup and played in the FIFA World Cup qualifiers, though it has never qualified for the World Cup.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain's national football team won the West Asian Football Federation cup and the Arabian Gulf Cup in 2019.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Both the cups came under the helm of Helio Sousa who is the manager of the nation's national football team.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain has its own top-tier domestic professional football league, the Bahraini Premier League.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] On 3 August 2020, the Kingdom of Bahrain bought a minority stake in the Paris F.C., a team that plays in France's second tier.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain's entry into the soccer club spurred criticism that the country is trying to whitewash its human rights record and this is another way of buying influence in Europe.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Basketball, rugby and horse racing are also widely popular in the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The government of Bahrain also sponsors a UCI WorldTeam cycling team, Bahrain Victorius, which participated in the 2017 Tour de France.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain has a Formula One race track, which hosted the inaugural Gulf Air Bahrain Grand Prix on 4 April 2004, the first in an Arab country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] This was followed by the Bahrain Grand Prix in 2005.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Bahrain hosted the opening Grand Prix of the 2006 season on 12 March of that year.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] Both the above races were won by Fernando Alonso of Renault.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The race has since been hosted annually, except for 2011 when it was cancelled due to ongoing anti-government protests.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The 2012 race occurred despite concerns of the safety of the teams and the ongoing protests in the country.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The decision to hold the race despite ongoing protests and violence has been described as "controversial" by Al Jazeera English, CNN, AFP and Sky News.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] *The Independent* named it "one of the most controversial in the history of the sport".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] In 2006, Bahrain also hosted its inaugural Australian V8 Supercar event dubbed the "*Desert 400*".
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The V8s returned every November to the Sakhir circuit until 2010, in which it was the second event of the series.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The Bahrain International Circuit also features a full-length dragstrip where the Bahrain Drag Racing Club has organised invitational events featuring some of Europe's top drag racing teams to try to raise the profile of the sport in the Middle East.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] On 10 June 2024, the Bahrain Olympic Academy received the Athena honorary distinction for its role in aiding and supporting advancement of sports in its region.
[src:archias-of-pella/bahrain-p03] The honorary medal was presented to his highness Shaikh Khalid bin Hamad Al Khalifa by Isidoros Kouvelos, President of IOA.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The **Euphrates** (/juːˈfreɪtiːz/ ⓘ *yoo-FRAY-teez*; see below) is the longest and one of the most historically important rivers of West Asia.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Together with the Tigris, it is one of the two defining rivers of Mesopotamia (lit.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Originating in Turkey, the Euphrates flows through Syria and Iraq to join the Tigris in the Shatt al-Arab in Iraq, which empties into the Persian Gulf.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Euphrates is the fifteenth-longest river in Asia and the longest in West Asia, at about 2,780 km (1,730 mi), with a drainage area of 440,000 km2 (170,000 mi2) that covers six countries.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The term *Euphrates* derives from the Greek *Euphrátēs* (Εὐφρᾱ́της), adapted from Old Persian: 𐎢𐎳𐎼𐎠𐎬𐎢, romanized: *hUfrātuš*, itself from Elamite: 𒌑𒅁𒊏𒌅𒅖, romanized: *Úipratuiš*.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Elamite name is ultimately derived from cuneiform 𒌓𒄒𒉣; read as *Buranun* in Sumerian and *Purattu* in Akkadian; many cuneiform signs have a Sumerian pronunciation and an Akkadian pronunciation, taken from a Sumerian word and an Akkadian word that mean the same.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Akkadian *Purattu* has been perpetuated in Semitic languages (cf.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Arabic: الفرات *al-Furāt*; Syriac: ̇ܦܪܬ *Pǝrāṯ*, Hebrew: פְּרָת *Pǝrāṯ*) and in other nearby languages of the time (cf.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Elamite, Akkadian, and possibly Sumerian forms are suggested to be from an unrecorded substrate language.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Gamkrelidze and Vyacheslav Ivanov suggest the proto-Sumerian **burudu* "copper" (Sumerian *urudu*) as an origin, with an explanation that Euphrates was the river by which copper ore was transported in rafts, since Mesopotamia was the center of copper metallurgy during the period.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Euphrates is called *Yeprat* in Armenian (Եփրատ), *Perat* in modern Hebrew (פרת), *Fırat* in Turkish, فرات in Ottoman Turkish and *Firat* in Kurdish.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Mandaic name is *Praš* (ࡐࡓࡀࡔ), and is often mentioned as *Praš Ziwa* (pronounced *Fraš Ziwa*) in Mandaean scriptures such as the *Ginza Rabba*.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The earliest references to the Euphrates come from cuneiform texts found in Shuruppak and pre-Sargonic Nippur in southern Iraq and date to the mid-3rd millennium BCE.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] In these texts, written in Sumerian, the Euphrates is called *Buranuna* (logographic: UD.KIB.NUN).
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The name could also be written KIB.NUN.(NA) or dKIB.NUN, with the prefix "d" indicating that the river was a divinity.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] In Sumerian, the name of the city of Sippar in modern-day Iraq was also written UD.KIB.NUN, indicating a historically strong relationship between the city and the river.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Euphrates is the longest river of West Asia.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] It emerges from the confluence of the Kara Su or Western Euphrates (450 kilometres (280 mi)) and the Murat Su or Eastern Euphrates (650 kilometres (400 mi)) 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) upstream from the town of Keban in southeastern Turkey.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Daoudy and Frenken put the length of the Euphrates from the source of the Murat River to the confluence with the Tigris at 3,000 kilometres (1,900 mi), of which 1,230 kilometres (760 mi) is in Turkey, 710 kilometres (440 mi) in Syria and 1,060 kilometres (660 mi) in Iraq.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The same figures are given by Isaev and Mikhailova.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The length of the Shatt al-Arab, which connects the Euphrates and the Tigris with the Persian Gulf, is given by various sources as 145–195 kilometres (90–121 mi).
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Both the Kara Su and the Murat Su rise northwest from Lake Van at elevations of 3,290 metres (10,790 ft) and 3,520 metres (11,550 ft) amsl, respectively.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] At the location of the Keban Dam, the two rivers, now combined into the Euphrates, have dropped to an elevation of 693 metres (2,274 ft) amsl.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] From Keban to the Syrian–Turkish border, the river drops another 368 metres (1,207 ft) over a distance of less than 600 kilometres (370 mi).
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Once the Euphrates enters the Upper Mesopotamian plains, its grade drops significantly; within Syria the river falls 163 metres (535 ft) while over the last stretch between Hīt and the Shatt al-Arab the river drops only 55 metres (180 ft).
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Euphrates receives most of its water in the form of rainfall and melting snow, resulting in peak volumes during the months April through May.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Discharge in these two months accounts for 36 percent of the total annual discharge of the Euphrates, or even 60–70 percent according to one source, while low runoff occurs in summer and autumn.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The average natural annual flow of the Euphrates has been determined from early- and mid-twentieth century records as 20.9 cubic kilometres (5.0 cu mi) at Keban, 36.6 cubic kilometres (8.8 cu mi) at Hīt and 21.5 cubic kilometres (5.2 cu mi) at Hindiya.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] However, these averages mask the high inter-annual variability in discharge; at Birecik, just north of the Syro–Turkish border, annual discharges have been measured that ranged from a low volume of 15.3 cubic kilometres (3.7 cu mi) in 1961 to a high of 42.7 cubic kilometres (10.2 cu mi) in 1963.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The discharge regime of the Euphrates has changed dramatically since the construction of the first dams in the 1970s.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Data on Euphrates discharge collected after 1990 show the impact of the construction of the numerous dams in the Euphrates and of the increased withdrawal of water for irrigation.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Average discharge at Hīt after 1990 has dropped to 356 cubic metres (12,600 cu ft) per second (11.2 cubic kilometres (2.7 cu mi) per year).
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The seasonal variability has equally changed.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The pre-1990 peak volume recorded at Hīt was 7,510 cubic metres (265,000 cu ft) per second, while after 1990 it is only 2,514 cubic metres (88,800 cu ft) per second.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The minimum volume at Hīt remained relatively unchanged, rising from 55 cubic metres (1,900 cu ft) per second before 1990 to 58 cubic metres (2,000 cu ft) per second afterward.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] In Syria, three rivers add their water to the Euphrates; the Sajur, the Balikh and the Khabur.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] These rivers rise in the foothills of the Taurus Mountains along the Syro–Turkish border and add comparatively little water to the Euphrates.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Sajur is the smallest of these tributaries; emerging from two streams near Gaziantep and draining the plain around Manbij before emptying into the reservoir of the Tishrin Dam.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Balikh receives most of its water from a karstic spring near 'Ayn al-'Arus and flows due south until it reaches the Euphrates at the city of Raqqa.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] In terms of length, drainage basin and discharge, the Khabur is the largest of these three.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Its main karstic springs are located around Ra's al-'Ayn, from where the Khabur flows southeast past Al-Hasakah, where the river turns south and drains into the Euphrates near Busayrah.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Once the Euphrates enters Iraq, there are no more natural tributaries to the Euphrates, although canals connecting the Euphrates basin with the Tigris basin exist.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The drainage basins of the Kara Su and the Murat River cover an area of 22,000 square kilometres (8,500 sq mi) and 40,000 square kilometres (15,000 sq mi), respectively.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Estimates of the area of the Euphrates drainage basin vary widely; from a low 233,000 square kilometres (90,000 sq mi) to a high 766,000 square kilometres (296,000 sq mi).
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The greater part of the Euphrates basin is located in Turkey, Syria, and Iraq.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] According to both Daoudy and Frenken, Turkey's share is 28 percent, Syria's is 17 percent and that of Iraq is 40 percent.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Isaev and Mikhailova estimate the percentages of the drainage basin lying within Turkey, Syria and Iraq at 33, 20 and 47 percent respectively.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Some sources estimate that approximately 15 percent of the drainage basin is located within Saudi Arabia, while a small part falls inside the borders of Kuwait.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Finally, some sources also include Jordan in the drainage basin of the Euphrates; a small part of the eastern desert (220 square kilometres (85 sq mi)) drains toward the east rather than to the west.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] In 2021, the Iraqi Ministry of Water Resources reported that the Euphrates river could dry out by 2040 due to climate change and droughts.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Euphrates flows through a number of distinct vegetation zones.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Although millennia-long human occupation in most parts of the Euphrates basin has significantly degraded the landscape, patches of original vegetation remain.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The steady drop in annual rainfall from the sources of the Euphrates toward the Persian Gulf is a strong determinant for the vegetation that can be supported.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] In its upper reaches the Euphrates flows through the mountains of Southeast Turkey and their southern foothills which support a xeric woodland.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Plant species in the moister parts of this zone include various oaks, pistachio trees, and *Rosaceae* (rose/plum family).
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The drier parts of the xeric woodland zone supports less dense oak forest and *Rosaceae*.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Here can also be found the wild variants of many cereals, including einkorn wheat, emmer, oat and rye.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] South of this zone lies a zone of mixed woodland-steppe vegetation.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Between Raqqa and the Syro–Iraqi border the Euphrates flows through a steppe landscape.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] This steppe is characterised by white wormwood (*Artemisia herba-alba*) and Amaranthaceae.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Throughout history, this zone has been heavily overgrazed due to the practicing of sheep and goat pastoralism by its inhabitants.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Southeast of the border between Syria and Iraq starts true desert.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] This zone supports either no vegetation at all or small pockets of *Chenopodiaceae* or *Poa sinaica*.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Although today nothing of it survives due to human interference, research suggests that the Euphrates Valley would have supported a riverine forest.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Species characteristic of this type of forest include the Oriental plane, the Euphrates poplar, the tamarisk, the ash and various wetland plants.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Among the fish species in the Tigris–Euphrates basin, the family of the Cyprinidae are the most common, with 34 species out of 52 in total.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Among the Cyprinids, the mangar has good recreational fishing qualities, leading the British to nickname it the "Tigris salmon".
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Euphrates softshell turtle is an endangered soft-shelled turtle that is limited to the Tigris–Euphrates river system.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Neo-Assyrian palace reliefs from the 1st millennium BCE depict lion and bull hunts in fertile landscapes.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Sixteenth to nineteenth century European travellers in the Syrian Euphrates basin reported on an abundance of animals living in the area, many of which have become rare or even extinct.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Species like gazelle, onager and the now-extinct Arabian ostrich lived in the steppe bordering the Euphrates valley, while the valley itself was home to the wild boar.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Carnivorous species include the wolf, the golden jackal, the red fox, the leopard and the lion.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Syrian brown bear can be found in the mountains of Southeast Turkey.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The presence of Eurasian beaver has been attested in the bone assemblage of the prehistoric site of Tell Abu Hureyra in Syria, but the beaver has never been sighted in historical times.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Hindiya Barrage on the Iraqi Euphrates, based on plans by British civil engineer William Willcocks and finished in 1913, was the first modern water diversion structure built in the Tigris–Euphrates river system.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Hindiya Barrage was followed in the 1950s by the Ramadi Barrage and the nearby Abu Dibbis Regulator, which serve to regulate the flow regime of the Euphrates and to discharge excess flood water into the depression that is now Lake Habbaniyah.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Iraq's largest dam on the Euphrates is the Haditha Dam; a 9-kilometre-long (5.6 mi) earth-fill dam creating Lake Qadisiyah.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Syria and Turkey built their first dams in the Euphrates in the 1970s.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Tabqa Dam in Syria was completed in 1973 while Turkey finished the Keban Dam, a prelude to the immense Southeastern Anatolia Project, in 1974.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Since then, Syria has built two more dams in the Euphrates, the Mansoura Dam and the Tishrin Dam, and plans to build a fourth dam – the Halabiye Dam – between Raqqa and Deir ez-Zor.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Euphrates Dam is Syria's largest dam and its reservoir (Euphrates Lake) is an important source of irrigation and drinking water.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] It was planned that 640,000 hectares (2,500 sq mi) should be irrigated from Euphrates Lake, but in 2000 only 100,000–124,000 hectares (390–480 sq mi) had been realized.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Syria also built three smaller dams on the Khabur and its tributaries.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] GAP affects a total area of 75,000 square kilometres (29,000 sq mi) and approximately 7 million people; representing about 10 percent of Turkey's total surface area and population, respectively.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] When completed, GAP will consist of 22 dams – including the Keban Dam – and 19 power plants and provide irrigation water to 1,700,000 hectares (6,600 sq mi) of agricultural land, which is about 20 percent of the irrigable land in Turkey.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] 910,000 hectares (3,500 sq mi) of this irrigated land is located in the Euphrates basin.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] By far the largest dam in GAP is the Atatürk Dam, located c.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] 55 kilometres (34 mi) northwest of Şanlıurfa.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] This 184-and-1,820-metre-long (604 and 5,971 ft) dam was completed in 1992; thereby creating a reservoir that is the third-largest lake in Turkey.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] With a maximum capacity of 48.7 cubic kilometres (11.7 cu mi), the Atatürk Dam reservoir is large enough to hold the entire annual discharge of the Euphrates.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Completion of GAP was scheduled for 2010 but has been delayed because the World Bank has withheld funding due to the lack of an official agreement on water sharing between Turkey and the downstream states on the Euphrates and the Tigris.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Apart from barrages and dams, Iraq has also created an intricate network of canals connecting the Euphrates with Lake Habbaniyah, Lake Tharthar, and Abu Dibbis reservoir; all of which can be used to store excess floodwater.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Via the Shatt al-Hayy, the Euphrates is connected with the Tigris.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The largest canal in this network is the Main Outfall Drain or so-called "Third River;" constructed between 1953 and 1992.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] This 565-kilometre-long (351 mi) canal is intended to drain the area between the Euphrates and the Tigris south of Baghdad to prevent soil salinization from irrigation.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] It also allows large freight barges to navigate up to Baghdad.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The construction of the dams and irrigation schemes on the Euphrates has had a significant impact on the environment and society of each riparian country.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The dams constructed as part of GAP – in both the Euphrates and the Tigris basins – have affected 382 villages and almost 200,000 people have been resettled elsewhere.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The largest number of people was displaced by the building of the Atatürk Dam, which alone affected 55,300 people.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] A survey among those who were displaced showed that the majority were unhappy with their new situation and that the compensation they had received was considered insufficient.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The flooding of Euphrates Lake led to the forced displacement of c.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] 4,000 families, who were resettled in other parts of northern Syria as part of a now abandoned plan to create an "Arab belt" along the borders with Turkey and Iraq.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Apart from the changes in the discharge regime of the river, the numerous dams and irrigation projects have also had other effects on the environment.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The creation of reservoirs with large surfaces in countries with high average temperatures has led to increased evaporation; thereby reducing the total amount of water that is available for human use.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Annual evaporation from reservoirs has been estimated at 2 cubic kilometres (0.48 cu mi) in Turkey, 1 cubic kilometre (0.24 cu mi) in Syria and 5 cubic kilometres (1.2 cu mi) in Iraq.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Water quality in the Iraqi Euphrates is low because irrigation water tapped in Turkey and Syria flows back into the river, together with dissolved fertilizer chemicals used on the fields.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The salinity of Euphrates water in Iraq has increased as a result of upstream dam construction, leading to lower suitability as drinking water.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The many dams and irrigation schemes, and the associated large-scale water abstraction, have also had a detrimental effect on the ecologically already fragile Mesopotamian Marshes and on freshwater fish habitats in Iraq.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The inundation of large parts of the Euphrates valley, especially in Turkey and Syria, has led to the flooding of many archaeological sites and other places of cultural significance.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Although concerted efforts have been made to record or save as much of the endangered cultural heritage as possible, many sites are probably lost forever.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The combined GAP projects on the Turkish Euphrates have led to major international efforts to document the archaeological and cultural heritage of the endangered parts of the valley.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Especially the flooding of Zeugma with its unique Roman mosaics by the reservoir of the Birecik Dam has generated much controversy in both the Turkish and international press.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The construction of the Tabqa Dam in Syria led to a large international campaign coordinated by UNESCO to document the heritage that would disappear under the waters of Euphrates Lake.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Archaeologists from numerous countries excavated sites ranging in date from the Natufian to the Abbasid period, and two minarets were dismantled and rebuilt outside the flood zone.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Important sites that have been flooded or affected by the rising waters of Euphrates Lake include Mureybet, Emar and Abu Hureyra.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] A similar international effort was made when the Tishrin Dam was constructed, which led, among others, to the flooding of the important Pre-Pottery Neolithic B site of Jerf el Ahmar.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] An archaeological survey and rescue excavations were also carried out in the area flooded by Lake Qadisiya in Iraq.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Parts of the flooded area have recently become accessible again due to the drying up of the lake, resulting not only in new possibilities for archaeologists to do more research, but also providing opportunities for looting, which has been rampant elsewhere in Iraq in the wake of the 2003 invasion.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] In Islamic tradition, a hadith of Muhammad states that the Last Hour will not occur until the Euphrates River uncovers a mountain of gold, over which people will fight.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Ninety-nine out of every one hundred individuals engaged in this conflict will perish.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] This event is considered one of the minor signs of the approaching Day of Judgment.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] In the Christian Bible, the Euphrates River is mentioned in Revelation 16:12: the Euphrates drying up is part of a series of events that foretell the Second Coming.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The river Phrath mentioned in Genesis 2:14 is also identified as the Euphrates, being one of the rivers of Paradise.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] In Jeremiah 46, the river is repeatedly mentioned as part of his prophecy and several other times throughout the bible either by name or by "the river" or "the great river".
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The early occupation of the Euphrates basin was limited to its upper reaches; that is, the area that is popularly known as the Fertile Crescent.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Acheulean stone artifacts have been found in the Sajur basin and in the El Kowm oasis in the central Syrian steppe; the latter together with remains of *Homo erectus* that were dated to 450,000 years old.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] In the absence of irrigation, these early farming communities were limited to areas where rainfed agriculture was possible, that is, the upper parts of the Syrian Euphrates as well as Turkey.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Late Neolithic villages, characterized by the introduction of pottery in the early 7th millennium BCE, are known throughout this area.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Occupation of lower Mesopotamia started in the 6th millennium and is generally associated with the introduction of irrigation, as rainfall in this area is insufficient for dry agriculture.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Evidence for irrigation has been found at several sites dating to this period, including Tell es-Sawwan.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] During the 5th millennium BCE, or late Ubaid period, northeastern Syria was dotted by small villages, although some of them grew to a size of over 10 hectares (25 acres).
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] In Iraq, sites like Eridu and Ur were already occupied during the Ubaid period.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Clay boat models found at Tell Mashnaqa along the Khabur indicate that riverine transport was already practiced during this period.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The Uruk period, roughly coinciding with the 4th millennium BCE, saw the emergence of truly urban settlements across Mesopotamia.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Cities like Tell Brak and Uruk grew to over 100 hectares (250 acres) in size and displayed monumental architecture.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] The spread of southern Mesopotamian pottery, architecture and sealings far into Turkey and Iran has generally been interpreted as the material reflection of a widespread trade system aimed at providing the Mesopotamian cities with raw materials.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Habuba Kabira on the Syrian Euphrates is a prominent example of a settlement that is interpreted as an Uruk colony.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] During the Jemdet Nasr (3600–3100 BCE) and Early Dynastic periods (3100–2350 BCE), southern Mesopotamia experienced a growth in the number and size of settlements, suggesting strong population growth.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] These settlements, including Sumero-Akkadian sites like Sippar, Uruk, Adab and Kish, were organized in competing city-states.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Many of these cities were located along canals of the Euphrates and the Tigris that have since dried up, but that can still be identified from remote sensing imagery.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] A similar development took place in Upper Mesopotamia, Subartu and Assyria, although only from the mid 3rd millennium and on a smaller scale than in Lower Mesopotamia.
[src:archias-of-pella/euphrates] Sites like Ebla, Mari and Tell Leilan grew to prominence for the first time during this period.
